<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="play">
<PB REF="7">
<HEAD>COLUMBUS: AN HISTORICAL PLAY.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT I.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE I.&mdash;<HI>On one &s;ide of the &s;tage a flight of &s;teps, with a Portico leading to the Temple of the Sun.&mdash;In the back|ground the &s;ea. Time, &s;un-ri&s;e.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE>Catalpo <HI>and Prie&s;ts from the Temple, who range them&s;elves&mdash;then enter</HI> Orozimbo&mdash;<HI>they bow to him as he pa&s;&s;es.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>OROZIMBO, <HI>pro&s;trating him&s;elf to the &s;un.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>SOUL of the univer&s;e, who from they glittering throne beame&s;t immortal &s;plendour, as thou ha&s;t permitted the &s;tars for their appointed hour to be&s;pangle the veil of night, now o'erwhelm all manner of glories in the greatne&s;s of thy efful|gence, and be once more welcom'd by thy de|voted &s;ervants to delight and ble&s;s the world!&mdash;Catalpo, conduct hither the virgin de&s;tined to re|ceive a prie&s;te&s;s' &s;acred office.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="2" REF="8">CATALPO <HI>exit, and re-enters with</HI> SOLASCO, <HI>lead|ing in</HI> CORA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sola&s;co </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(kneels.)</STAGE>
<P>Mighty chief!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimba.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ri&s;e, good Sola&s;co.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sola&s;co.</SPEAKER>
<P>I here pre&s;ent the darling of my age to be devoted to the &s;ervice of our god. It will be wor&s;e than parting with my life to lo&s;e the com|forts of her dear &s;ociety&mdash;but the bright &s;un, our glorious deity, demands &s;uch excellence to be con&s;igned alone to do <HI>him</HI> honour.&mdash;Pardon, my king, an old man's tears; but nature will not al|ways, without a &s;truggle, yield to duty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou ha&s;t, indeed, devoted to thy god a precious trea&s;ure; but tell me, Cora, can thy youthful mind freely re&s;ign the livelier joys of &s;ocial life, and re&s;t contented in &s;eclu&s;ion and tranquillity?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>My father's will has ever &s;way'd my thoughts, from the fir&s;t hour that infant &s;en&s;e cou'd learn obedience:&mdash;Should he doom my death, his mandate would be met with equal re|&s;ignation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thy pious mind, which knows to yield &s;uch duty to a father, will well befit the &s;er|vice of thy god.&mdash;But hear the &s;acred tenour of the law which binds a prie&s;te&s;s to her duty.&mdash; Should the heart, to heaven devoted, become the prey of &s;acrilegious love, our law con&s;igns its prie&s;te&s;s, and the accomplice of her guilt, to in|&s;tant death. Her parents and their offspring are pledges for her faith, and &s;hould her flight elude offended ju&s;tice, their forfeit lives mu&s;t expiate her crime. <STAGE>[Cora <HI>bows to the &s;un.</HI>]</STAGE> Now to the altar, and record your vows; then, as our cu&s;tom is, come forth to &s;hine Queen of this fe&s;tive day,
<PB N="3" REF="9">the la&s;t you are to know exempt from &s;acred duty.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt</HI> Cora, Sola&s;co, <HI>and</HI> Prie&s;ts, <HI>to the Temple.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>During the latter part of this &s;cene the &s;un becomes ob&s;cured by clouds, and thunder and lightning i&s;&s;ue from them&mdash;the &s;ea much agitated.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Catalpho.</SPEAKER>
<P>Great chief, behold what envious clouds ob&s;cure the glories of our god.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Say, Catalpo, what mean the&s;e bo|dings! <STAGE>A &s;hip appears from behind a projecting rock.</STAGE> And lo!&mdash;What mon&s;ter's that, who&s;e wings bear it buoyant on the angry main?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>A cannon is di&s;charged from the &s;hip.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Catalpo.</SPEAKER>
<P>See!&mdash;From its throat thunder and fire bur&s;t forth, &s;eeming to brave high heaven.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be not di&s;may'd&mdash;&s;ummon our war|riors. <STAGE>[<HI>to</HI> Cuto.]</STAGE> Catalpo, let the prie&s;ts attend.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE II. <HI>The Country.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Orozimbo <HI>meeting</HI> Cuto, <HI>Warriors, and Indians.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>My people, we'll to the &s;hore&mdash; Should they prove mortal foes, we'll meet their thunders, or if the engines of infernal power, what can virtue fear?&mdash;Tru&s;t me, the Deity we &s;erve, will re-a&s;&s;ume his &s;plendour, and protect his cho&s;en people.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE III. <HI>A View of an Indian Country.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter in proce&s;&s;ion, Indian Officer&mdash;Warriors&mdash;Indian Mu&s;ic&mdash;Cuto&mdash;Archers&mdash;Standard of the Sun&mdash; Cora&mdash;Prie&s;ts of the Sun&mdash;Indians bearing pre|&s;ents and Banners&mdash;Nelti&mdash;Indian Women bear|ing
<PB N="4" REF="10">Pre&s;ents&mdash;Warriors&mdash;Orozimbo in a Car, burni&s;hed with Gold, &s;upported on the &s;houlders of Indians, and attended by Nobles with golden Staves &mdash;Warriors.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE IV. <HI>The Sea Coa&s;t.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE>Three Ships are &s;een at anchor, and Boats come to Shore with martial Mu&s;ic and Colours flying.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter from the Boat,</HI> Columbus, Alonzo, Roldan, Valverdo, Harry Herbert, <HI>and the re&s;t of the Spani&s;h Adventurers.</HI>&mdash;Columbus <HI>lands fir&s;t, with his Sword drawn&mdash;he falls and embraces the Earth, during which Time there are three Cheers, and a di&s;charge of Artillery; then the re&s;t follow and come forward.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fir&s;t, to high Heaven, who thus, with never-fading honour, hath crown'd its poore&s;t &s;ervant, let me pour forth a heart o'erwhelm'd with gratitude. And now begin the important work which heaven has delegated to us&mdash;Erect the &s;acred banner of our faith.</P>
<STAGE>The Cro&s;s is erected on one &s;ide of the &s;tage.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Brave a&s;&s;ociates! join with me in prai&s;e of him, who hath atchiev'd what ignorance, with &s;apient &s;hrug, and &s;atisfied, benumbing prudence derided as the chimera of a madman's fancy: falling at his feet, let us be proud in being fir&s;t to pay due homage to &s;uch &s;urpa&s;&s;ing excellence.</P>
<STAGE>They all kneel.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ri&s;e, ri&s;e;&mdash;rather, my Alonzo, in the&s;e arms receive my thanks, thou, next to heaven, my firme&s;t friend. Ye men of Spain, let what has pa&s;&s;ed admoni&s;h you in what may be to come&mdash;keep in your minds the time when we had gained the cour&s;e which &s;hut out the ea&s;tern world; how you beat your brea&s;ts, op|pre&s;&s;ed
<PB N="5" REF="11">with fear and &s;uper&s;tition&mdash;How, with womani&s;h tears, you bade adieu to life, and blub|bered out a requiem for your &s;ouls; then em|bracing de&s;peration in&s;tead of fortitude, I was to be your &s;acrifice; and this body, which has been your conduct to wealth and honour, you would have given to the &s;ea, and ignorance and cow|ardice would have triumphed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Valverdo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mighty Sir, forgive us!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Freely, good Valverdo&mdash;Let the man &s;tand forth, who, at a time &s;o fraught with peril, fir&s;t di&s;covered land.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[Coming forward.]</STAGE>
<P>It was my good fortune.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou art not a Spaniard.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, your Excellency, I am an Eng|li&s;hman; and tho' we Engli&s;hmen are an odd, whim&s;ical &s;et of fellows, yet we generally con|trive (and I tru&s;t ever &s;hall) to keep a good look out a-head when our &s;uperior is in danger.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tell me your fortunes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>My name is Harry Herbert; I am de|&s;cended from as re&s;pectable and independent an ance&s;tor as the world can boa&s;t, &mdash; an Engli&s;h yeo|man; but the civil wars leaving my family little, which my imprudence &s;oon made le&s;s, I thought that, altho' King Henry was deprived of the honour of this enterprize, that did not preclude his &s;ubjects; &s;o I &s;hipped my&s;elf off for Ca&s;tille, where I had ju&s;t time and ca&s;h enough to fall a dozen times in love, and into other &s;erapes, be|fore I had the honour of embarking on board your Excellency's &s;quadron.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Herbert, thou do&s;t honour to thy country.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, Sir, I am glad, that for once I
<PB N="6" REF="12">am even with it; for I am &s;ure my country does honour to me.</P>
<STAGE>Indian mu&s;ic without.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Behold a crowd of people, many of whom &s;eem clad in &s;acred ve&s;tments&mdash;Their dre&s;s and &s;tandards be&s;peak them greatly civilized, and full of wealth.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter in proce&s;&s;ion Indian Warriors, bearing a Standard of the Sun</HI>&mdash;Orozimbo, Cora, &amp;c.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[De&s;cends from his car.]</STAGE>
<P>Strangers, who &s;eem to be above the race of mortals, in&s;truct us how to honour you&mdash;If you be children of the Sun, behold our prie&s;ts, who with perfumes and libations, will welcome you to his holy temple; or, if human, here are fruits to feed you, dwell|ings to &s;helter you, and garments to clothe you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Chief, you behold in us the children of mortality; but the power we &s;erve, in his high mercy, has be&s;towed upon us &s;uperior gifts; thus, thro' unknown &s;eas to brave the imperious &s;urge, and to con&s;truct engines which can &s;weep thou&s;ands from the earth&mdash;But that Deity com|mands us to proclaim his name with peace&mdash;The King, our ma&s;ter, wi&s;hes to enrich thee and him|&s;elf &mdash;this hardy metal, u&s;eful in all the purpo&s;es of life, he will exchange for tho&s;e thy country may produce.</P>
<STAGE>Pre&s;ents a hatchet.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis very &s;trange&mdash;Thy King much wrongs him&s;elf&mdash;all we have to render is our gold, but that we find &s;o yielding, and &s;o u&s;ele&s;s, it were an injury to offer it&mdash;Indulge the curio&s;ity of a &s;tranger.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Orozimbo, <HI>with</HI> Columbus, Roldan, Her|bert, Nelti, Catalpo, <HI>&amp;c. move up the &s;tage.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oft has a tender glance e&s;cap'd my eye, impell'd by Beauty's power, and from my bo&s;om
<PB N="7" REF="13">the &s;oft &s;igh in&s;tinctively has &s;tolen&mdash;Many a fair Ca&s;tilian has enforced this te&s;t of admiration, but now my every &s;en&s;e &s;eems drawn by power magnetic to that lovely &s;aint&mdash;Permit me, faire&s;t creature, to expre&s;s my admiration at the charms which now pre&s;ent them&s;elves&mdash;tho' all the won|ders of a new di&s;covered world di&s;play their rival novelties, yet, now that I behold its fir&s;t of won|ders, all el&s;e exacts from me as little notice, as I, I fear, have power or merit to command from you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Strange you wrong your&s;elf, and hold me un&s;kilful to di&s;tingui&s;h, when you &s;uppo&s;e de&s;ert like yours can pa&s;s unnoticed&mdash;Your prai&s;es of the humble Cora, tho' they have cau&s;ed no vain emotion, yet ever will the mind receive with plea|&s;ure, prai&s;e e'en unmerited, when 'tis be&s;towed by tho&s;e who claim our admiration.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>All that the warme&s;t fancy can depict in the bright colours of ideal excellence, can never reach that exqui&s;ite perfection nature ex|hibits &mdash;how mu&s;t I ble&s;s my happy fortune, that bore me to a clime which boa&s;ts an or|nament like thee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<P>What new emotion ri&s;es in my brea&s;t&mdash;I fear to a&s;k my heart from whence it &s;prings. Oh, Cora! think of thy &s;acred duty&mdash; think of the vow which pa&s;s'd thy lips &s;o lately.&mdash; Stranger, tho' &s;acred ho&s;pitality commanded me to pay this courte&s;y, yet now a higher duty en|joins me to de&s;i&s;t from further conver&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let me entreat one in&s;tant&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>It mu&s;t not be&mdash;my conduct is controlled by rigid laws. Farewell.&mdash;Oh Cora, what days of wretchedne&s;s art thou doom'd to &s;uffer!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>A&s;ide, as &s;he retires to the prie&s;ts. Alonzo.</STAGE>
<SP>
<PB N="8" REF="14">
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>What cou'd &s;he mean? "Her con|duct is controlled by rigid laws"&mdash;If &s;he be de&s;|tined to another, my lot is mi&s;ery.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[with <HI>Columbus,</HI> coming forward.]</STAGE>
<P>In harmony and peace I rule a free and happy people, and I were unworthy of my kingdom, did I not endeavour to the utmo&s;t to convert the name of &s;tranger into friend.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>[Exeunt</HI> Orozimbo <HI>and</HI> Columbus, <HI>hand in hand; Prie&s;ts follow; then</HI> Alonzo, Roldan, Val|verdo, &amp;c. <HI>and the Spani&s;h and Indian &s;oldiers &mdash;One party bow to the cro&s;s, the other to the &s;un.]</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Manent</HI> Herbert <HI>and</HI> Nelti.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o, my pretty Indian, you live very happily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, all the day long.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>And have you no monks who pray for you, di&s;pute with you, and burn you alive when you don't think as they do?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! no.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor devils, what a way they mu&s;t be in.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't you come from the other world?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, you &s;ee &s;omething angelic about me, eh!&mdash;Yes, my love, I come from a little paradi&s;e, call'd England.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is England a world?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>A bit of one; but, little as it is, it &s;omehow contrives to manage all the re&s;t.&mdash; Shou'd you like to live in England?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>O yes; I &s;uppo&s;e Engli&s;h women, arm'd with &s;pears made of that pretty, hard iron, climb the mountains, and de&s;troy the wild bull.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>De&s;troy the wild bull! No, my dear; our Engli&s;h women find prettier amu&s;ement in
<PB N="9" REF="15">encouraging the breed of horned cattle&mdash;the u&s;e of the pretty, hard iron is confined to the men, and no great favourite there; for I know many flouri&s;hers of &s;pontoons, who have a cur&s;ed antipathy to cold iron.&mdash;Who is that elegant creature you were conver&s;ing with?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Her name is Cora; &s;he was this day ad|mitted a prie&s;te&s;s of the Sun.&mdash;The hand&s;ome&s;t virgins are always &s;elected to &s;u&s;tain that &s;acred office.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>The hand&s;ome&s;t! you were then, on that account, not&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did I &s;ay the hand&s;ome&s;t? Oh dear, I mean they &s;elect the mo&s;t &s;edate&mdash;for, from this day &s;he mu&s;t never leave the temple, or conver&s;e with any except the prie&s;ts.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Except the prie&s;ts! Go where you will, you find tho&s;e gentlemen always contrive to be well taken care of&mdash;would you like to be|come a prie&s;te&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[&s;ighing.]</STAGE>
<P>La&s;t night perhaps I &s;hould.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Charming &s;en&s;ibility! and may I, my &s;weet girl, interpret that &s;igh in my favour?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, you will not love me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not love thee!&mdash;By Magna Charta, I'll re&s;ign my life, fortune, and liberty to thee.&mdash; be&s;ides, I'll bring thee beads, cloathes, mu&s;ic&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, that is not love.&mdash;They only try to plea&s;e the eye, who find their actions cannot touch the heart.&mdash;no pre&s;ents or toys could in|fluence Nelti.&mdash;no, not if you were to give her an iron javelin and a tame tiger.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed!&mdash;very delicate pre&s;ents for a young lady.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<P>I wi&s;h I cou'd make him love me&mdash; how do women in England gain their lover's hearts?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Generally by u&s;ing them like dogs.&mdash; for, when a woman &s;tudiou&s;ly avoids looking at
<PB N="10" REF="16">a man, abu&s;es him on all occa&s;ions, and is kind to every one el&s;e, we naturally conclude they love each other to di&s;traction.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti .</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide]</STAGE>
<P>I never can find in my heart to u&s;e him ill&mdash;What ugly thing is that?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Dolores <HI>and</HI> Bribon, <HI>from a boat.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>A doctor of phy&s;ic, who having killed all his patients in the old world, except his wife, who wou'd never take his medicines, has ven|tured hither, in pur&s;uit of new patients, new fees, and perhaps a new bed-fellow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>And what's the other?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>A lawyer and a coxcomb.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's a coxcomb?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>A reptile, my dear, that is found in abundance in all countries, and yet is not ea&s;ily de&s;cribed&mdash;it is a kind of mongrel, which men drive from them, becau&s;e they hardly con&s;ider it as belonging to them, and the women won't re|ceive, becau&s;e they think it won't breed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>All &s;eems pretty quiet.&mdash;I &s;ay, Bri|bon&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>What do you &s;ay, Doctor Dolores?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>This &s;eems cur&s;ed mild, whole&s;ome, unprofitable air for a phy&s;ician.&mdash;But heaven is merciful, wherever I go, patients increa&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>There &s;eems plenty of gold, and plen|ty of gold, plenty of law, follows as naturally as a bill of co&s;ts.&mdash;I &s;ay, Doctor, do you &s;ee that &s;weet, pretty, wealthy-looking girl&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>I fancy I &s;hall have &s;ome pretty fe|male practice here.&mdash;I was a great favourite in Spain; for my maxim was, always to &s;tick to my friends to the la&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Doctor, welcome to the new world.&mdash; So, you kept on board till all was quiet.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="11" REF="17">
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure&mdash;con&s;ider the importance of my life to you all; but my chief rea&s;on was, that the famous a&s;trologer, Doctor Diego Diab|la&s;co, told me &s;omething ill would happen if I were ra&s;h&mdash;but there &s;eems no danger&mdash;that's a very pretty girl, and I love a fine young girl, al|mo&s;t as much as I do fine old gold</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>And have you, Doctor, &s;o &s;oon forgot your old helpmate in Valladolid?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, poor old Dorothy! But, Lord, I hate con&s;tancy as much as I hate health <STAGE>[addre&s;&s;ing Nelti.]</STAGE> Permit me, &s;weete&s;t of &s;avages, to enquire after the &s;tate of your health&mdash;how is your pul&s;e? let me feel how it beats&mdash;beats.&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>Takes her hand.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Feel how it beats? Perhaps it beats harder than you think</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then there's the more nece&s;&s;ity I &s;hould feel it, my pretty, pretty&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>There, then.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Strikes him.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zounds! a dozen &s;uch patients wou'd do for me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Doctor, I hope to be honoured with the <HI>hand</HI> of this charming girl.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, with all my heart&mdash;I'm &s;ure <HI>I've</HI> had enough of it&mdash;but you can't marry her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, thou profe&s;&s;or of the glorious art of man&s;laughter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e the Pope allows no religious ceremonies with hereticks&mdash;all dealings with them mu&s;t be in the way of plunder and glorious in|trigue.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Pope! p&s;haw&mdash;I &s;hall &s;it down here for life, contented with a little&mdash;I'll build a neat, convenient hou&s;e, after the fa&s;hion of the country, with a plain &s;ilver door, and a diamond knocker. The apartments &s;hall be merely lined
<PB N="12" REF="18">with plates of gold, neatly carved&mdash;the &s;ophas of &s;ilver ti&s;&s;ue, and &s;tuffed with the down of hum|ming-birds &mdash;As for fre&s;co-work of emeralds, ru|bies, pearls, amethy&s;ts, and &s;uch nicknacks, my wife may ornament her dairy and dre&s;&s;ing-room with them&mdash;in &s;hort, I'll have every thing in a &s;nug, comfortable way, without &s;hew or expence</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Without &s;hew or expence!&mdash;Pray, great Sir, &mdash;will you allow a poor man to gather up the chips, and now and then take a peep into your <HI>golden</HI> apartments?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Dolores, by the time I build, I fancy you'll have a &s;nug <HI>leaden</HI> apartment of your own&mdash;&s;o, go count beads in&s;tead of ducats, and try not to cheat <HI>young</HI> Harry out of his mi&s;tre&s;s, but <HI>old</HI> Harry out of your &s;oul.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt</HI> Herbert <HI>and</HI> Nelti.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zounds! let's follow; for who knows, but in a minute, the&s;e &s;avages may knock my brains out, with one of your &s;hin-bones.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come along&mdash;Oh, I wi&s;h I had the doctoring of you for a week, you Engli&s;h ma&s;tiff.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>END OF THE FIRST ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="act">
<PB N="13" REF="19">
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE I.&mdash;<HI>The Spani&s;h Camp.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Columbus, <HI>with a party of &s;oldiers, guarding others, chained, meeting</HI> Roldan <HI>and</HI> Valverdo.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>UNGRATEFUL men, thus, in a moment, to de&s;troy my brighte&s;t hopes.&mdash;&s;ee them clo&s;ely guarded.</P>
<STAGE>Exeunt Soldiers, guarded.</STAGE>
<P>Roldan, would thou think it, tho&s;e wretches (dead to prudence as to honor) have damn'd the name of Spaniard, they have reviled the Indian prie&s;ts, and with unmanly outrage, have torn away the golden ornamen's that decked the love|ly brea&s;ts of innocence.&mdash;The men, exa&s;perated, call to the Cacique for vengeance; I, at the ha|zard of my life mu&s;t follow, and appea&s;e his ju&s;t re&s;entment.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Valverdo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shall then a brave Ca&s;tilian be di&s;|graced with bonds, for &s;hewing di&s;re&s;pect to vile idolatry?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Valverdo.&mdash;Soon &s;hall this up|&s;tart Genoe&s;e, Columbus, feel the ju&s;t vengeance of in&s;ulted Spain <STAGE>[&s;hewing a paper].</STAGE>&mdash;My brother in ambition, look on this paper.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Valverdo.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's this&mdash;the royal &s;ignature?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mark me.&mdash;When our gracious Queen embraced the fortunes of this foreign Viceroy,
<PB N="14" REF="20">even proffered her regal ornaments to equip his fleet, the mini&s;ter, Fone&s;ca, jealous of the fame that might attend this enterpri&s;e, worked on the fears of the &s;u&s;picious Ferdinand, to execute this commi&s;&s;ion of control, which, now Columbus' conduct gives pretence, arrays me with the power of cru&s;hing his authority, and with di&s;grace re|turning him to Spain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Valverdo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Glorious hearing!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do thou, Valverdo, tamper with the troops, &mdash;pre&s;s on their &s;uper&s;titious minds the in|jury our faith will &s;uffer by winking at idolatry; tell them, the way to &s;udden wealth is ea&s;y, had they a fit commander&mdash;in&s;inuate&mdash;but we wa&s;te words&mdash;about it, good Valverdo.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> Valverdo.</STAGE>
<P>'Twere pre&s;umption to in&s;truct a monk in wiles of glozing cozenage.</P>
<STAGE>Retires up the &s;tage.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Alonzo.</STAGE>
<P>The fatal wound is given to all my hopes&mdash;what years of bli&s;s had my &s;oul fondly pictured as Alon|zo's lot&mdash;Oh, lovely Cora, mu&s;t then thy beau|ties never more beam their bright radiance on me? &mdash;Had'&s;t thou been doom'd to fill another's arms, I had indeed been cur&s;ed, but not &s;o deeply; for I might &s;till have gazed upon thy heavenly form &mdash;have li&s;tened to the &s;weet melody of thy loved voice, and known delight even in mi&s;ery&mdash;But all is gloomy horror now before me.</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope I not untimely interrupt your meditations.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Roldan, the conduct of the&s;e Indians ob&s;cures our European virtues, and we are come to be in&s;tructed, not to teach&mdash;The good Colum|bus has appea&s;ed their ju&s;t re&s;entment, and, at the reque&s;t of Orozimbo, con&s;ents to liberate the pri&s;oners.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="15" REF="21">
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis well <HI>[&s;hews a plan of attack]</HI> but as we mu&s;t &s;ecure a place of &s;afety (for it were madne&s;s to repo&s;e confidence in &s;avages) here have I drawn a plan which mu&s;t render the town an ea&s;y capture.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>The town a capture!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do&s;t thou not under&s;tand me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope I do not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>There is no &s;afety but in their de&s;truc|tion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Roldan, thou &s;urely can'&s;t not be &s;o damn'd as think it&mdash;What, &s;tab the fond heart which overflows with love and adoration for thee&mdash; trample down &s;acred ho&s;pitality, and erect the throne of treachery and murder&mdash;by the great God of ju&s;tice, fir&s;t thro' this body thou mu&s;t force thy way, thou traitor to humanity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Soft-hearted fool, the&s;e mawki&s;h vir|tues have ever been the &s;ainted garb of cowards.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Coward!</P>
<STAGE>They fight.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Cuto, <HI>with Indians, who ru&s;h in between'em.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cuto.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thanks to the God, this arm receiv'd the &s;troke that wou'd have &s;lain thee.</P>
<STAGE>To Roldan.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Good youth, thou bleed'&s;t&mdash;Pray take all care of him <STAGE><HI>[binds his handkerchief round</HI> Cuto'<HI>s arm]</HI></STAGE> Roldan, if yet thou need'&s;t a &s;timulus to virtue, look on that Indian, and in the name of heaven, &s;tain not thy honour and thy man|hood with treachery and ingratitude.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fortune permits thee now to &s;chool me&mdash;but, boy, thou &s;halt feel my power; go to the Viceroy, tell him that Roldan lacketh bro|therly affection for the poor Indians, and add (for by the power of vengeance it is true) that Rol|dan is his covenanted foe&mdash;that he hath given
<PB N="16" REF="22">freedom to tho&s;e Ca&s;tilians he dared di&s;grace with bonds, and that, by thee, he greets his Excellency with defiance and contempt.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit Roldan.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Perfidious, bloody villain! Oh, my friends, dangers I fear await you&mdash;I blu&s;h to &s;ay we have among us tho&s;e who&s;e vilene&s;s your pure nature cannot image. Let us prepare to meet the wor&s;t&mdash;&s;ummon your warriors, while I in|&s;truct them how be&s;t to guard each place of 'van|tage&mdash;and &s;hould this Roldan attempt to execute his villainous intent, depend on the protection of Columbus.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> Alonzo, <HI>with Indians.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE II. <HI>A Retired Place.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Columbus.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>All happine&s;s is mingled with alloy&mdash; I've triumphed over every oppo&s;ition malice and folly rai&s;ed to check my glory&mdash;I, now, in Eu|rope's eye &s;hall &s;tand arrayed in all the honours which &s;ucce&s;s commands&mdash; <Q REND="margQuotes">tho&s;e, who if acci|dent had thwarted my rea&s;on-founded &s;chemes would with important ignorance have &s;coffed at the &s;illy vague projector&mdash;will now, with pane|gyric full as thoughtle&s;s, admire my courage, and applaud my pre&s;cience</Q>&mdash;yet, when I have at|tained the &s;ummit of my wi&s;hes, when I &s;hou'd give &s;ome little re&s;t to my care-worn mind, which long has &s;truggled with adver&s;ity; when I might contemplate with joy, the virtues I have found in this new world, virtues more rare than all the riches it abounds in, &mdash;I &s;ind I have conducted to this haple&s;s &s;pot, hearts black with di&s;content, and factious jealou&s;y, thir&s;ting for plunder and for blood! But if determined rigour&mdash;virtuous example&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="17" REF="23"><HI>Enter</HI> Herbert, <HI>running.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>May it plea&s;e your Excellency&mdash;I beg your excu&s;e;&mdash;but I am &s;o choaked with rage, and breathle&s;s with running, that I have &s;carce power to tell you&mdash;your troops have mu|tinied.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mutinied! Explain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Roldan, Sir, that&mdash;but I know a &s;ol|dier's duty too well, to &s;peak ill of a &s;uperior officer, or I'd tell your Excellency what a cur&s;ed inhuman &s;coundrel I think him&mdash;Their villainy and ingratitude is beyond belief&mdash;they murmur that you won't give them leave to cut the throats of the&s;e innocent Indians&mdash;They call for Roldan to head them, and I'll do him the ju&s;tice to &s;ay, he would let them indulge in &s;uch pretty, harmle&s;s diver&s;ion, as long as there was a throat left in the country.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>This demands my in&s;tant pre&s;ence&mdash; Herbert, in half an hour, attend me at the camp.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, if I had that Roldan in England, I'd hang him up without judge or jury&mdash;tho', on recollection, I have fixed on the wor&s;t place in the world for hanging folks up, becau&s;e a great man like me wills it&mdash;<Q REND="margQuotes">but now for vengeance&mdash; and yet I don't know how it happens, that al|tho' in &s;ome things I am a tolerably active, in|du&s;trious fellow, yet when I have to &s;eek re|venge, I grow &s;o infernally lazy I can &s;carce find in my heart to &s;et about it.</Q></P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="18" REF="24">
<HEAD>SCENE III.&mdash;<HI>The Sea Coa&s;t&mdash;a boat &s;tationed.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Roldan, <HI>with Troops, meeting</HI> Valverdo.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>May I tru&s;t that look propitious&mdash;Oh, let thy words confirm it&mdash;how ha&s;t thou pro&s;|pered with the &s;oldiers?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Valverdo.</SPEAKER>
<P>They more than met my wi&s;hes, and the da&s;tard few, whom con&s;cience kept in doubt, I &s;oon won over by the &s;timulus of plun|der, &s;piced with our Church's di&s;pen&s;ation&mdash;in a word, they have all &s;worn, that on a &s;ignal given, they will de&s;ert Columbus.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>And in an hour, to a fairer promi&s;er, wou'd they abandon <HI>me.</HI>&mdash;It mads me that I mu&s;t climb the heights of proud ambition on the &s;houlders of &s;uch a crew of mongrels.&mdash;My de|&s;ign is to &s;end Columbus, loaded with chains and accu&s;ation, a pri&s;oner to Spain, and with him, tho&s;e hen-hearted fools, who&s;e &s;uper&s;titious &s;cru|ples might prove trouble&s;ome.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Valverdo.</SPEAKER>
<P>With deference to your happier po|licy, do you not ri&s;k by this the wrath of I&s;abella?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not a whit. For, unle&s;s Valverdo, thou ha&s;t made &s;ome &s;aint thy enemy, who, in mere &s;pite, may work for them a miracle, they'll not fatigue the royal ear with much complain|ing. &mdash;To be plain, the ve&s;&s;el which &s;hall convey them hence, is &s;o &s;trained, crazy, and unfit for &s;ervice, &s;he cannot weather out the &s;lighte&s;t &s;torm, therefore, the fir&s;t rude wind that blows, will &s;end them to explore <HI>another</HI> world.&mdash;But hark, that trumpet &s;peaks Columbus.&mdash;Now, fortune, be my friend.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="19" REF="25"><HI>Enter</HI> Columbus, Mo&s;co&s;o, <HI>and Troops.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Roldan, what means this outrage, this trea&s;on to thy King? Why &s;pur on to de&s;|peration and rebellion, your few mi&s;taken fol|lowers, whom my power, did I not abhor revenge, could in an in&s;tant &s;weep from the earth?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Columbus, on <HI>thee</HI> let me retort the name of traitor.&mdash;I &s;tand here, cho&s;en by the general voice, the avenger of their wrongs.&mdash; 'Tis thee they charge with trea&s;on to their King, a&s;&s;ert thou wink'&s;t at here&s;y, and ha&s;t made them the &s;laves of &s;avages.&mdash;How do&s;t thou an&s;wer?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Herbert.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>An&s;wer to thee?&mdash;Roldan, pre&s;s not my patience farther.&mdash;But to convince thee, trai|tor, how fal&s;e are thy a&s;per&s;ions, and that I reign &s;overeign in my people's love&mdash;mark me, be this the te&s;t. <STAGE><HI>[Takes a &s;pear from one of the &s;ol|diers, and throws it between him and</HI> Roldan, <HI>di|viding the &s;tage.]</HI></STAGE> Let all, who do not in their hearts believe I mean them fairly, and judge thee worthier to command them, pa&s;s that jave|lin without fear or doubt.&mdash;Be that the barrier betwixt my influence and thine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Much it glads me thou ha&s;t proffered &s;o fair a trial; and I &s;wear, if they approve thee, I will re&s;ign into thy hand my &s;word and life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now, my brave &s;oldiers, hear my firm intent; I will lead you on to wealth, but not by ma&s;&s;acre; I'll make you all, the wonders of the world, rich and beloved.&mdash;Then, without controul, decide your fate; but, remember, &mdash;you have but one &s;tep to make from honor to di&s;|grace.</P>
<STAGE>[Valverdo, <HI>and tho&s;e on</HI> Columbus's <HI>&s;ide, pa&s;s over to</HI> Roldan.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="20" REF="26">
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be it &s;o&mdash;men without hearts are not worth regretting.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Herbert, <HI>who has been &s;tanding on</HI> Roldan's <HI>&s;ide, after eyeing with contempt tho&s;e who de|&s;erted</HI> Columbus, <HI>pa&s;&s;es between the front of the &s;tage and</HI> Roldan, <HI>to</HI> Columbus.]</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Great Sir, accept my humble &s;ervices. &mdash;de&s;pi&s;e not him, who honours you&mdash;pray ex|cu&s;e the&s;e tears&mdash;let me embrace your knees.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Falls, and embraces his knees.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>My heart! my heart!&mdash;Herbert, thy gratitude unmans me,</P>
<STAGE>Embraces him.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now, Columbus, look on that paper; by it thou'lt find thy King di&s;tru&s;ted thee <STAGE>[giving the paper.]</STAGE> And pray you all remember, I ex|erted not the high authority of which my &s;ove|reign thought me worthy, 'till he was de&s;erted, and de&s;pi&s;ed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Peace, fiery indignation;&mdash;down re|bel heart, &mdash;and do not choak my utterance.&mdash; Well, Viceroy, <STAGE>[giving his &s;taff to Roldan]</STAGE> where are your racks, &mdash;your in&s;truments of vengeance?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, do not fear&mdash;we mean no torture.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>And think'&s;t thou, villain, the &s;ub|tile&s;t inqui&s;itor, who has out-damn'd his fellows in inventive cruelty, could give a pang like that I feel, in &s;eeing thee po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ed of power to make the happy wretched?&mdash;Oh my poor Indians, who &s;hall now defend you, when this traitor, fit leader of his band of daemons, like the arch-fiend, new lighted on a world of innocence, &s;hall diffu&s;e his devili&s;h &s;pirit, and extend hell's empire.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bring forth his chains <STAGE>[Columbus is chained]</STAGE>&mdash;for &s;o the King enjoin'd he &s;hou'd be &s;ent to Spain whenever he proved unworthy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="21" REF="27">
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Chains! Hell and fury <STAGE>[draws his &s;word, but is di&s;armed]</STAGE> Confu&s;ion!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Captain, ob&s;erve that with &s;trict atten|tion you obey your orders, <STAGE>[pointing to Herbert]</STAGE>&mdash; for that &s;tubborn rebel&mdash;bear him to torture.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold, Roldan&mdash;thy vengeance mu&s;t be mo&s;t complete when I de&s;cend to a&s;k a favour from thee&mdash;let my humility glut thy vin|dictive wrath.&mdash;Allow that Engli&s;hman to &s;hare my fortunes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bear him away.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Roldan, a wretch like thee &s;hould have a coward's caution.&mdash;Do&s;t thou not dread, that in his dying moments, when, in defiance of thy tortures, (for I can read his noble &s;oul,) he braves thee to the la&s;t, and glories in a death of honour, do&s;t thou not fear he may infect this ruffian crew with &s;ome faint &s;parks of hone&s;ty, and make them le&s;s fit in&s;truments for thee?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bear him to death.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heaven pre&s;erve your Excellency.&mdash; Will you, great Sir, conde&s;cend to indulge the la&s;t wi&s;h of vanity, and, when you have nothing el&s;e to do, write to England the &s;tory of my fate; that when my fortunes &s;hall be enquired af|ter, my friends, with joy &s;parkling thro' a tear, may &s;ay, Herbert &s;tuck to his commander to the la&s;t, and died as an Engli&s;hman ought.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>My noble fellow, this hand &s;hall ju&s;|tify thy fame.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I am ea&s;y.&mdash;May your portion of happine&s;s be equal to your virtues&mdash;farewell. &mdash; <STAGE><HI>[To</HI> Roldan.]</STAGE> Perhaps, Sir, you never were at the death of an Engli&s;h game-cock.&mdash;Will you do me the favour of attending my execution?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="22" REF="28">
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Take him from my &s;ight.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hands off, reptiles! <STAGE><HI>[to</HI> Roldan.]</STAGE> That you are the mo&s;t infernal &s;coundrel the devil ever made a friend of, all your worthy a&s;&s;ociates about you will, I dare &s;ay, allow&mdash;but I brand you with the name of fool, for enabling an humble man like me, thus to triumph over you, to defy you&mdash; &s;corn you&mdash;laugh at you&mdash;Hands off, reptiles!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> Herbert, <HI>guarded.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[to Roldan]</STAGE>
<P>Is then my triumph for a world's di&s;covery, and the trophies which I bear to Spain, to tell attending crowds my glory, a body bowed by ignominious fetters?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Captain.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pardon me, Sir, if I pre&s;ume to beg, that I may &s;o far mitigate their rigour, as when on board, to free the noble pri&s;oner from their weight.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>You know not what you a&s;k&mdash;wi&s;h me to forfeit the honours my King has heaped on me&mdash;no, the&s;e are his gracious gifts, and I've not yet learnt to di&s;obey him&mdash;and here I vow before that power who cheers the &s;oul of &s;uffering virtue, tho' their cankerous rivets corrode my very bones, no hand but Ferdinand's &s;hall free me from them&mdash; By heaven, my &s;oul pants for the moment, when thus accoutered, I may meet his pre&s;ence, and a&s;k him&mdash;how I have de&s;erved the&s;e favours from him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Officer.</SPEAKER>
<P>All is ready.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bear him then on board.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt</HI> Roldan <HI>and Troops.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou guardian of the innocent, to thy &s;upreme protection I commend the generous natives of this haple&s;s land; a&s;&s;i&s;t them to defend
<PB N="23" REF="29">their liberties from the fell gra&s;p of this dete&s;ted crew&mdash;To them extend thy mercy; and let me pour my thanks for that cele&s;tial fortitude which glows within my brea&s;t&mdash;with it I can defy the &s;torms of fortune, &s;afe in the approval of a guilt|le&s;s mind, which, not de&s;erving wrong, can never feel di&s;grace.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt</HI> Columbus <HI>and Attendants to the Boat.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Orozimbo, Alonzo, <HI>and Indian Warriors.</HI>&mdash; Alonzo <HI>ru&s;hes to the top of the Stage.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Great chief, your &s;uccours come too late&mdash;alas! he's gone! Oh! for vengeance on that traitor, Roldan;&mdash;may this arm drive him from the earth, which groans at bearing &s;uch a wretch, and hurl him to the infernal gulph, as yet untenanted by any fiend &s;o cur&s;ed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo, do&s;t thou not blu&s;h to call the&s;e wretches, countrymen, who &s;purn at &s;acred virtue, and &s;eem to court pre-eminence in perdition.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Spain, thou ha&s;t lo&s;t thy glory&mdash;pride and fanatici&s;m have rear'd their bloody banner, and virtue flies to foreign climes for &s;helter&mdash; Orozimbo, to thee and to thy country I dedicate my life&mdash;Hark! <STAGE>[Cannon di&s;charged]</STAGE> The cannon's ireful throat, wont proudly to proclaim defiance, now throws along the wave a &s;olemn &s;ound, as knolling a departed friend.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Herbert <HI>without his Cloak and Doublet.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have e&s;caped the blood-hounds&mdash; Zounds! how I &s;campered&mdash;I never before knew
<PB N="24" REF="30">I was &s;o eminently gifted with that fa&s;hionable military accompli&s;hment, retreating.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>What means this &s;trange appearance?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll tell you&mdash;that cannibal, Roldan, was, I believe, a little inclined to be dainty, and, wi&s;hing for a choice bit, con&s;igned me over to Valverdo, who &s;tood man-cook on the occa&s;ion&mdash; he ordered me to be &s;cored like pork, and then to be roa&s;ted; and the humane prie&s;t remarked, there was not &s;o excellent a receipt for in&s;uring the love of heaven, as taking half a dozen here|ticks and broiling them gently over a &s;low fire&mdash; Acknowledge Roldan Viceroy, &s;ays he&mdash;I'd &s;ee you damn'd fir&s;t, &s;ays I&mdash;&s;o, watching my op|portunity, I gave the prie&s;t a Corni&s;h hug, &s;hewed his &s;cullions a &s;pecimen of Engli&s;h wre&s;tling, and off I came, tru&s;&s;ed for dre&s;&s;ing, as you &s;ee me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, my brave friend, thou then wilt aid our cau&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you &s;uppo&s;e that I, who had my forefathers chopped to atoms in deciding the pre|ference between a red ro&s;e and a white one, will &s;tand idle in the cau&s;e of humanity?&mdash;No, give me a &s;word, and if I don't, without benefit of clergy, execute that prie&s;t, Valverdo, whom the devil has &s;ent hither as his plenipotentiary, make me commander in chief to all the cowards in Europe.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[to Orozimbo.]</STAGE>
<P>Act in pur&s;uance of the plan I gave, and with a rampart circle in the town, then let but hunger, that harbinger of mu|tiny once a&s;&s;ail them, they, like oppo&s;ing poi&s;ons, will &s;oon de&s;troy each other, and &s;ave your darts the labour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="25" REF="31">
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tru&s;t me, brave people, the&s;e gods are vulnerable&mdash;&s;oon &s;hall you behold your ja|velins burni&s;hed with their blood&mdash;hunger and thir&s;t is their's as well as our's, and the &s;oul of a Spaniard takes its flight from a wound, as &s;wiftly as an Indian's&mdash;Lead on.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>END OF THE SECOND ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="act">
<PB N="26" REF="32">
<HEAD>ACT III.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE I.</HI>&mdash;The Temple of the Sun.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Catalpo <HI>and Prie&s;ts a&s;&s;embled round the Altar. Enter</HI> Orozimbo <HI>and</HI> Alonzo.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>MATCHLESS infamy! how could the vil|lain Roldan think &s;o poorly of me? the tender of his friend&s;hip was &s;ufficient in&s;ult, without the terms on which he offers it. Re&s;ign thee to him! purcha&s;e by treachery the friend|&s;hip of a traitor, &mdash;and for what? Had he the power to rai&s;e me above all the glories ambition ever coveted, &s;hould I not, after &s;uch a crime, &s;it pining 'mid&s;t my &s;plendour, the victim of ac|cu&s;ing con&s;cience, finding a cur&s;e in every ble&s;&s;ing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>My heart burns with impatience to lead your valiant troops to ju&s;t revenge&mdash;but let vigilance and caution guide us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>My friend, do thou direct us at thy will&mdash;<HI>[to the prie&s;ts]</HI>&mdash;prepare the rites, the &s;a|crifice for war, and let the prie&s;te&s;s who was la&s;t received a &s;ervant of the Sun, approach the altar with her &s;acred pre&s;ent.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>The prie&s;ts range round the altar&mdash;folding-doors open, and prie&s;te&s;&s;es enter and range on each &s;ide</HI>&mdash; Cora <HI>enters, bearing offerings in a golden ba&s;ket.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<PB N="27" REF="33">
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q REND="margQuotes">'Tis &s;he&mdash;'tis Cora&mdash;&s;upport me, heaven&mdash;this unexpected &s;ight o'erpowers me.</Q>&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[not &s;eeing <HI>Alonzo,</HI> advances and kneels at the altar.]</STAGE>
<P>Thou, glorious Sun, accept our hum|ble offerings&mdash;receive with favour the righteous homage of our grateful hearts&mdash;If thy children e'er have broken the laws of ho&s;pitality, if ever they have failed to greet a &s;tranger with a bro|ther's love, they nor de&s;erve, nor dare to hope thy fatherly protection&mdash;but if they have not merited the wrongs they &s;uffer, pre&s;erve&mdash;protect them!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>[Prie&s;ts and prie&s;te&s;&s;es pro&s;trate them&s;elves;&mdash;</HI> Catalpo <HI>takes from the altar an Indian weapon, and gives it to</HI> Cora.]</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Catalpo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Prie&s;te&s;s, bear to our chief this con&s;e|crated weapon, it &s;hall defend the Sun's in&s;ulted glory, our &s;overeign's, and his people's rights.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Cora <HI>receives the weapon, and in bearing it to</HI> Orozimbo, <HI>&s;ees</HI> Alonzo&mdash;<HI>exclaims,</HI> &mdash;"Oh, heavens!"&mdash;<HI>drops the weapon, and faints&mdash;</HI> Alonzo <HI>endeavours to a&s;&s;i&s;t her.]</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Catalpo. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[to Alozo.]</STAGE>
<P>Forbear&mdash;the proffered kindne&s;s claims our thanks; but thy unhallowed hand wou'd be a profanation to a prie&s;te&s;s' &s;acred per&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>What means this tremor?&mdash;What &s;hock &s;o &s;uddenly has &s;truck that lovely frame?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know not&mdash;a momentary weakne&s;s&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Cora <HI>is borne off by the prie&s;te&s;&s;es.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let all attention wait her&mdash;'tis but the effect of apprehen&s;ion from her inexperience in her &s;acred office&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="28" REF="34">
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>She &s;eemed much agitated&mdash;How &s;hall I bear this aggregate of mi&s;ery&mdash;my agony I fear will &s;peak, what &s;hou'd be hid from all.&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[to the prie&s;ts.]</STAGE>
<P>Conclude your rites; and may the power &s;upreme accept our fervent prayers, and be our humble offerings grateful to him.</P>
<STAGE>[The Scene clo&s;es.]</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE II.</HI> An Indian Town.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Dolores <HI>and</HI> Bribon.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you, this new world is crammed with wizzards and a&s;trologers, that whiz about in the night time, rai&s;ing &s;torms, tempe&s;ts, and mi&s;chief; and can tell the day a man is to die, with as much certainty as&mdash;as&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>As you can the death of your own pa|tients.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>And can prolong your life year after year as ea&s;ily&mdash;as you can a law-&s;uit.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>But what cur&s;ed luck it is to be cooped up here with a parcel of &s;avages, who know as much of litigation, as I do of the war-whoop&mdash; here I &s;ee gold enough to make me a judge; but I can't get a bit big enough to buy a &s;crap of parchment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cur&s;e the new world, I &s;ay&mdash;there is not a man in it wants a phy&s;ician but my&s;elf&mdash; If I cou'd but have gone back with Columbus&mdash; he mu&s;t by this time be near Spain, and perhaps old Dorothy's dead.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Nelti.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[&s;ighs.]</STAGE>
<P>Shall I never &s;ee my dear En|gli&s;hman
<PB N="29" REF="35">again? He plea&s;es my heart when pre|&s;ent, but ah, how he plagues it when ab&s;ent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Singular ca&s;e&mdash;always plagued my wife when pre&s;ent, plea&s;ed her when ab&s;ent.&mdash; <STAGE>[addre&s;s|ing Nelti]</STAGE> Mo&s;t amiable and wealthy &s;avage, be|hold a lawyer and a chri&s;tian, who will give you the fee &s;imple of his heart, and receive in return, all your love, and <STAGE>a&s;ide]</STAGE> all your money.&mdash;Doctor, I wi&s;h to join i&s;&s;ue here&mdash;I'll employ you as coun&s;el, &mdash;&s;ay &s;omething for me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will&mdash;I will&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[apart to</HI> Nelti.]</STAGE> My dear, beautiful goldfinch, that fellow is a wicked, cheating lawyer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ee he's doing my bu&s;ine&s;s for me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look with an eye of commi&s;eration on one who loves thee.&mdash;Oh, how I long to ki&s;s tho&s;e pouting lips.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>You ugly creature, if you touch me, I'll cry out.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<P>Cry out, ha, ha!&mdash;when a wo|man declares &s;he will cry out, and when I &s;ay I will give a man a ducat to &s;ave him from &s;tarving, I believe we are both apt to be cur&s;edly wor&s;e than our words&mdash;come, one bu&s;s&mdash;Oh lud, oh lud! how much in love I am!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>You old propagator of poi&s;ons, is this the way you plead my cau&s;e? By heaven, my dear, that old a&s;&s;a&s;&s;in has killed more than all the bravoes in Spain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is a Doctor a bravo?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, my dear, with an univer&s;ity edu|cation&mdash;why, you old idol of grave-diggers, have not you confounded all di&s;tinction between a pre|&s;eription and a death-warrant&mdash;had not you a re|gular
<PB N="30" REF="36">annuity from the undertakers&mdash;have not you cheated me out of thou&s;ands, by making people die &s;o fa&s;t, I had not time to make their wills?&mdash;here's a pretty fellow to make love to a &s;weet girl&mdash;Why, he's as blind as ju&s;tice, as un|feeling as a whipping-po&s;t, as di&s;ea&s;ed as a laza|retto, and as old as a chancery &s;uit.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, you Janus-faced villain&mdash;What, traduce my fame?&mdash;was not I always a favourite with the women?&mdash;when their hu&s;bands were ill, did not the dear creatures always &s;end for me? &mdash;had not I the honour of receiving a gold medal from the inqui&s;ition for keeping a man alive nine days, during the mo&s;t excruciating torture?&mdash; and did not I cure you of a crick in the neck, which you got by &s;tanding in the pillory, you one-ear'd ra&s;cal?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yonder I &s;ee Herbert, and &s;hou'd he find you here&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>He, I &s;uppo&s;e, wou'd make his cane join i&s;&s;ue with my head&mdash;I ab&s;cond.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, you cowardly villain! what, run away&mdash;egad, I'll be off too.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[alone]</STAGE>
<P>Now I'm alone, I'll practice &s;uch behaviour as, I am told, the women in the other world u&s;e, that I may win the heart of my dear Engli&s;hman.&mdash;Fir&s;t then, I mu&s;t avoid him&mdash; certainly&mdash;but that I'll do &s;ome other time&mdash;then I mu&s;t abu&s;e him&mdash;true, but how!&mdash;Oh, were it my ta&s;k to prai&s;e, how prodigal would this heart be in pouring forth its &s;tore, which niggard now, will not afford one har&s;h idea. But I mu&s;t try&mdash; ah, yonder he comes&mdash;well, I'm quite indifferent
<PB N="31" REF="37">whether I &s;ee him or not&mdash;I'll not walk in his way, I'm determined.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Retires up the &s;tage.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Herbert.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>It's always my infernal luck to be in a rage&mdash;to think that the&s;e innocent people, who lived as happily before the Spaniard's came, as the people in a village do before an attorney comes among them&mdash;&s;hould now have gridirons for beds&mdash;and what they think wor&s;e&mdash;the Spa|niards place on their bodies, which were as free as Engli&s;hmens&mdash;an indelible mark of &s;lavery.&mdash; Oh, I hope nobody will contradict me to day&mdash;I wi&s;h I could &s;ee Nelti&mdash;her &s;oothing fondne&s;s would&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>Nelti pa&s;&s;es him [&s;inging.]</STAGE>
<P>Ah, Nelti, how do you do? <STAGE>[loud.]</STAGE>&mdash;My love! my love!!</P>
<STAGE>[louder.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is it you? I declare I did not ob&s;erve you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;what might you be thinking of, my dear?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>That &s;uperior being, the elegant Alonzo.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>You were? and pray what might in|duce you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heigho!</P>
<STAGE>[&s;ighs.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>My &s;weet girl, I'll tell you what. I have been in a mo&s;t infernal rage, and I am not &s;ure it is quite abated&mdash;&s;o, to prevent mi&s;takes, ki&s;s me, &mdash;and, if you plea&s;e, we'll have no jokes at pre&s;ent; for, tho' I love joking pretty well, I love ki&s;&s;ing a devili&s;h deal better.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[apart]</STAGE>
<P>What a charming effect unkindne&s;s
<PB N="32" REF="38">has&mdash;I'll even give him plenty on't&mdash;really, Sir, you mu&s;t po&s;&s;e&s;s a con&s;iderable &s;hare of vanity, in &s;uppo&s;ing there is no object worthy my regard but you&mdash;don't deceive your&s;elf&mdash;you, &mdash;whom Do|lores &s;ays, kicked the women, and were kicked by the men.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>He &s;aid that, did he? When I have the honour of meeting him, I'll try whether I have forgot my kicking. But&mdash;zounds, did not you tell me you adored me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>But then I had &s;carcely &s;een the elegant Alonzo, the &s;age Dolores,&mdash;be&s;ides, that was &s;ome time ago.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Whew !!! Oh, there mu&s;t be &s;ome mi&s;take&mdash;certainly one of the wizards old Do|lores talks of mu&s;t have been bu&s;y here&mdash;but come, Nelti, have done with folly, and tell me you love me &s;incerely.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h I cou'd&mdash;but&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damn your <HI>buts,</HI> yon imp of mi&s;|chief, what do you mean?&mdash;have you encouraged me one day, to make my mortifications greater the next? have I left the jilts of one world to find the &s;ame whirligig tricks in another&mdash; don't provoke me, or, by St. George and his dragon, I'll&mdash;damnation, that a man can't, with honour, beat any woman but his wife.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh dear, I have gone too far&mdash;Harry, Harry!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Keep out of my way, or by all the heroes in England I &s;hall never contain my&s;elf&mdash; don't come near me, talk of me, or think of me&mdash; Go to Alonzo, &mdash;go to the doctor, or go to the devil; and as long as you are as mi&s;erable as I wi&s;h you, dam'me if I care where you go&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<PB N="33" REF="39">
<SPEAKER>Nelti </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[crying.]</STAGE>
<P>I find I don't know how to u&s;e a man ill&mdash;I was a fool for trying it&mdash;I can't tell how Engli&s;h women manage&mdash;but I am very &s;ure I was made to u&s;e men kindly.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE IV.&mdash;<HI>The Spani&s;h Camp. [Night.]</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Mo&s;co&s;o <HI>and Spaniards, with booty.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mo&s;co&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>Our commander Roldan, mu&s;t not think of &s;haring in this trea&s;ure&mdash;damn &s;ubordi|nation&mdash;are not we Chri&s;tians &s;uperior beings? and have not we a right to murder as many In|dians as we think fit?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Spaniard.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, to be &s;ure; if they won't be|come Chri&s;tians quietly, we mu&s;t broil them till they do.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Spaniards, pulling in</HI> Cuto.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d Spaniard.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is the &s;aucie&s;t Indian we have caught yet&mdash;all good words are thrown away upon him, &s;o, bring in the rack.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mo&s;co&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, be content to work and become a &s;lave, and we'll &s;hew you how to live.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cuto.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, give me your tortures, and I'll &s;hew you how to die.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Roldan.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>The hour &s;eems big with horror, and the vivid lightning, blazons the murky mantle of the night with awful &s;plendour&mdash;Mo&s;co&s;o, why are you ab&s;ent from your guard?&mdash;carry that gold to my tent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mo&s;co&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>I won't&mdash;I tell you what, Viceroy, my
<PB N="34" REF="40">maxim is this, &mdash;always to obey my commander to the la&s;t drop of my blood, while he lets me have my own way&mdash;why, you are not in Spain! by St. Lucifer, I won't part with the gold, &s;o, what &s;ignifies oppo&s;ition, when you know you can't help your&s;elf?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Columbus, how fully art thou now revenged&mdash; <STAGE>[a&s;ide]</STAGE>&mdash;execrable wretch!&mdash;but we are friends&mdash;the common &s;afety requires obe|dience, and only to pre&s;erve you all from death, I venture to oppo&s;e your wills.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mo&s;co&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, I am &s;atisfied&mdash;I am of a &s;weet di&s;po&s;ition&mdash;I have murdered many a man without bearing him the lea&s;t ill will.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who is that Indian?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mo&s;co&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't know; but he's a damn'd &s;aucy one, and minds no more <HI>dying,</HI> than we do <HI>killing him.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Has the torture extorted no &s;ecrets from him?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mo&s;co&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>We have not began to pinch him yet.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>A noi&s;e is heard, with thunder and lightning.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>What means this horrid noi&s;e? The earth trembles.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mo&s;co&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, mercy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cowards, proceed to extort confe&s;&s;ion from that reptile.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mo&s;co&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>I won't touch a hair of his head&mdash;do you think I am a &s;avage? how the ground &s;hakes!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Noi&s;e again.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>This war of elements is aweful, and may make the&s;e half-formed villains &s;queami&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mo&s;co&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>Could you find in your heart to tor|ture
<PB N="35" REF="41">a poor fellow-creature? We'll relea&s;e that Indian.</P>
<STAGE><HI>[To</HI> Roldan.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Roldan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, be it &s;o.&mdash; <STAGE>[Cuto <HI>is relea&s;ed, and exit.</HI></STAGE> But let not &s;ouls like yours be daunted; 'tis not the fir&s;t tempe&s;t you have witne&s;&s;ed&mdash;cheerly, my friends.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mo&s;co&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>I think its quite gone off&mdash;bring that ra&s;cally Indian back, we'll&mdash; <STAGE>Noi&s;e increa&s;es.</STAGE> Oh, mercy! why, this is an earthquake.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Spaniard.</SPEAKER>
<P>Earthquake&mdash;aye, a terrible one.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mo&s;co&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>The earth &s;eems ready to open and &s;wallow us up&mdash;let us find the prie&s;t and get ab|&s;olution&mdash;Oh, mercy! mercy!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="5" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE V.</HI>&mdash;A view of the Temple of the Sun. In the back ground a mountain.</HEAD>
<STAGE>[Thunder and lightning.]</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Alonzo.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where'er I turn, 'tis ruin all and death. The wrath of heaven, rou&s;ed at the crimes it views, pours forth its mighty vengeance.&mdash; <Q REND="margQuotes">Oh God of ju&s;tice&mdash;may thy awful power bury within that earth their &s;ins incumber, all who for thir&s;t of gold forget humanity, dare to make thy &s;acred name a &s;anction for their crimes.</Q>&mdash;In this hour of horror, how does my anxious heart beat for her fate, who never can be mine&mdash;this tem|ple's hated walls encircle all that on earth could make me ble&s;t&mdash;but how can I approach her, and
<PB N="36" REF="42">to remain uncertain of her &s;afety, is wor&s;e than death <STAGE>[a har&s;h noi&s;e, and part of the mountain is di&s;|lodged.]</STAGE> &mdash;E'en now, perhaps, the earth entombs its riche&s;t trea&s;ure. <STAGE>[A turret of the temple is thrown down]</STAGE>&mdash;The dreadful &s;hock increa&s;es.&mdash;Spare, &s;pare my Cora!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>A violent cra&s;h&mdash;a part of the temple is thrown down&mdash;through the cha&s;m</HI> Cora <HI>is &s;een clinging to a column</HI>&mdash;Alonzo <HI>runs in, and bears her out &mdash;&s;he faints.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Revive, revive, my angel! let no fears a&s;&s;ail that &s;potle&s;s bo&s;om&mdash;Turn not from him, who, 'mid&s;t this &s;hock of nature, knows no ter|ror but for thee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Whither am I borne? What art thou? Tell me&mdash;'tis he, 'tis he&mdash;the con&s;tant object of my thoughts!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Has Cora e'er be&s;towed a thought on on her Alonzo."&mdash;Oh joy unhoped for.&mdash; <Q REND="margQuotes">In this dread hour to &s;hare thy fate was all my utmo&s;t wi&s;hes could a&s;pire to&mdash;but now to hear thee own a mutual flame, is bli&s;s which bears my raptured mind almo&s;t beyond the check of rea&s;on.</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>How my heart beats at this unlooked-for meeting.&mdash;How little could I hope to be thus ble&s;s'd a few &s;hort minutes &s;ince, when I expected death at every rude commotion&mdash;yet, even then, on thee my thoughts were fixed&mdash;thee I im|plored to aid me, and my la&s;t &s;igh would have breathed ble&s;&s;ings on thee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh my Cora, how &s;hall I tell thee what I feel at this exce&s;s of tenderne&s;s. <STAGE>A violent &s;hock, and a Volcano emits its fury.</STAGE>
<PB N="37" REF="43">Ha! heaven! my joy had bani&s;hed from my thoughts all fear; and mu&s;t we, mu&s;t we, at a time like this, glut the devouring earth, or drown in floods of fire&mdash;let's fly to &s;eek for &s;afety.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Safety&mdash;'tis here <STAGE>[throwing her&s;elf into his arms].</STAGE>&mdash;within thy arms I dread no danger.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>My heaven of bli&s;s, to die in thy em|brace, death would have no power to inflict a pang, but thy dear life is all I have to hope of happine&s;s on earth, and heaven direct me to pre&s;erve it.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>END OF THE THIRD ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="act">
<PB N="38" REF="44">
<HEAD>ACT IV.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE I.</HI>&mdash;A rich country with an arbour.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Alonzo <HI>and</HI> Cora <HI>di&s;covered.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>MY Cora, methinks I never lived till now&mdash; all that has pa&s;&s;ed of life, has been a dull journey to this point of happine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo&mdash;Oh, how that name vibrates thro' every nerve; and makes &s;uch &s;weet com|motion in each pul&s;e, as tho' they &s;welled to emulate my lips, and &s;trove to utter it.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>How my fancy glows with all the hap|pine&s;s which awaits us&mdash;we'll fly together to the dear retreats, where nature reigns with uncon|trolled dominion&mdash;there, free from every care which dwells with bu&s;y, artificial life, each day &s;hall greet us with unclouded joy, and each new hour &s;hall bring increa&s;e of bli&s;s&mdash;there &s;hall the dear delights of hu&s;band and of father&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Alonzo!</P>
<STAGE>[&s;he is near fainting]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why droops my love?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Father, &s;aid'&s;t thou?&mdash;that word has from my lethargy rou&s;ed me to madne&s;s&mdash;What have I done?&mdash;Love has with tyrant power &s;ub|dued my &s;oul, and forced from my fond mind each &s;en&s;e of duty and each tie of nature&mdash;where
<PB N="39" REF="45">&s;hall I fly?&mdash;where has the earth a place to hide a wretch like me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do not di&s;tract me, Cora&mdash;explain the&s;e terrors&mdash;be quick to tell me, that my heart may &s;hare in every pang of thine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Doom'd to the cruell'&s;t lot of human mi|&s;ery, hear all the horrors of my fate&mdash;when I, with heart which ne'er had felt one &s;en&s;e of pa&s;|&s;ion which it glows with now, gave up my future days to holy &s;olitude, <Q REND="margQuotes">that I by &s;uch a &s;acrifice, might heap more honours on a father's head than e'en his virtues could procure him</Q>&mdash;I then (Oh, heaven) &s;hould love e'er prove my con|queror, con&s;igned my&s;elf to death, e'en thee, Alonzo, that ra&s;h oath condemned thee too.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cea&s;e to bewail without a cau&s;e&mdash;a few &s;hort hours will bear us from the dread of all the terrors which oppre&s;s thy fear-&s;truck fancy&mdash; then ha&s;te, my love.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Whither, Alonzo?&mdash;What, leave my haple&s;s father and my &s;i&s;ters to expiate my crime &mdash;they are &s;ureties for me&mdash;my flight would doom their innocence to bleed for my offence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>What do&s;t thou utter?&mdash;Am I&mdash;am I the author of &s;uch direful ruin&mdash;am I the mur|derer of thy guiltle&s;s race?&mdash;did not affection check my ireful arm&mdash;did not my love command me to exi&s;t to &s;hare thy doom, whatever fate de|cree it, no longer wou'd I &s;truggle with the hor|rors that I feel, but part with life and mi&s;ery to|gether.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is this the comfort thou can&s;t give to Cora?&mdash;Ah, why talk I of comfort&mdash;comfort's the lot of innocence&mdash;&s;hall guilt like mine&mdash;&s;hall blind di&s;tracted pa&s;&s;ion, hope to feel the dear
<PB N="40" REF="46">felicity that virtue feels&mdash;Leave me, Alonzo, and pre&s;erve thy&s;elf; then let me fly to meet the wor&s;t of deaths, &s;o I may &s;pare my honoured fa|ther's life, and &s;ave the offspring which has not di&s;graced him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, cea&s;e, in pity cea&s;e&mdash;let not thy frantic de&s;peration drive thee to certain ruin.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo, can'&s;t thou coun&s;el parricide&mdash; would'&s;t thou receive a murderer to thy arms?&mdash; Lead me to the temple.&mdash;The tumult of the night may have pre&s;erved my flight unknown&mdash;then let me ha&s;te.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mu&s;t I re&s;ign thee&mdash;mu&s;t we part&mdash; <STAGE>[taking her hand]</STAGE> Oh, Cora, how hard a fate is ours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo, if parting thus with thee, or in&s;tant death were left me to decide on, how &s;hould I &s;purn exi&s;tence &s;o dearly to be purcha&s;ed. &mdash;But, oh, my father&mdash;my &s;i&s;ters&mdash;then let de&s;pairing love prey on my heart&mdash;the angui&s;h of remor&s;e &s;hall never reach it.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE II.&mdash;<HI>The out&s;ide of the Temple.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Alonzo and Cora, <HI>with great caution.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have beheld no creature, all &s;eems as &s;till, as if the late convul&s;ive &s;hock of nature had &s;pared no beings but our&s;elves.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>For what a fate Alonzo, are we &s;pared: &mdash;let me not think, or all my re&s;olution will for|&s;ake me&mdash;Leave me before I well can realize our parting; for if I give &s;cope to the dire thought, madne&s;s or death mu&s;t rob me of all thought.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="41" REF="47">
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will not, cannot &s;ay farewell; for yet, propitious heaven may ble&s;s us with each other.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! Alonzo, no more&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Alonzo <HI>leads her to the temple&mdash;they embrace&mdash; &s;he goes into the temple.&mdash;He exit on one &s;ide of the &s;tage.]</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE VI. <HI>The town.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Herbert <HI>and</HI> Nelti <HI>with a Quipos.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q REND="margQuotes">Forgive thee, my angel&mdash;name not the word&mdash;I like a woman to be a little whim&s;ical in trifles, as long as &s;he has the &s;ta|mina of affection at bottom&mdash;I am for none of your &s;till, quiet, good &s;ort of women, that make a man's life one continued dead calm&mdash; no&mdash;no&mdash;refre&s;hing breezes for me&mdash;when one is &s;ure not to be driven by them on the rocks of aver&s;ion, they render the voyage of life free from languor and in&s;ipidity&mdash;</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Re&s;t a&s;&s;ured every future breath of mine &s;hall &s;peak only affection and e&s;teem&mdash;but, my Herbert, to owe my life to thy protecting arm, is &s;uch joy, as makes me, &s;pite of its awful hor|rors, ble&s;s la&s;t night, which thus re&s;tor'd thee to my aching heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>My charming girl! Egad, I thought it was all over with us.</P>
</SP>
<Q REND="margQuotes"><SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Herbert! what unea&s;y hours have I pa&s;&s;ed, and what melancholy thoughts have been put into my head&mdash;look here&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>[&s;hewing the Quipos.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="42" REF="48">
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who gave you this&mdash;what do you call it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>One of our necromancers.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Necromancers&mdash;ha! ha! ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Every body believes in them&mdash;they &s;ay they can rai&s;e &s;torms and thunder&mdash;can tell who&s;e lives are joined together&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lives joined together&mdash;a curious doctrine&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>But I'll never tru&s;t them again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, my dear, tru&s;t only to me, and you'll certainly not have to deal with a <HI>conjuror.</HI></P>
</SP></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here come tho&s;e frights, Dolores and Bribon&mdash;I &s;hou'd like to plague 'em dearly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shou'd you, you rogue.&mdash;Egad, what you have told me about necromancers, and the &s;trange opinion of your country, that people's lives are joined together, has given me an idea which will plague them confoundedly, <Q REND="margQuotes">for their credulity in a&s;trology is equal to their profe&s;&s;ional ignorance.</Q>&mdash;This way, and I'll explain.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Retire up the &s;tage.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Dolores <HI>and</HI> Bribon, <HI>quarelling.</HI></STAGE>
<Q REND="margQuotes"><SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why do you keep following me, and chattering your cur&s;ed jargon&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll walk where I like, and talk what I like&mdash;</P>
</SP></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>"Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q REND="margQuotes">Very true&mdash;as nature here a&s;&s;erts her rights, of cour&s;e monkies have privilege to chatter without fear of correction, but</Q> to
<PB N="43" REF="49">compare your paltry profe&s;&s;ion with the noble art of healing?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, to &s;ay the truth, Doctors do put people out of their mi&s;ery.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, that's better than lawyers, who put them into mi&s;ery, and leave them there.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Call in a phy&s;ician, he kills, or nature cures.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>True; but call in a lawyer, and egad, kill or cure, right or wrong, is equally fatal&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[&s;eeing</HI> Herbert.]</STAGE>&mdash;Zounds! there's Herbert&mdash; tu&s;h, be quiet&mdash;let's li&s;ten.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Herbert <HI>and</HI> Nelti <HI>come forward.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>You amaze me! Can it be po&s;&s;ible that your necromancers are &s;o very potent?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>True indeed, my love.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>This union of lives is very wonder|ful, and doubtle&s;s very true&mdash;If old Dolores knew that his life depended on another's fate, how anxious wou'd he be to know who&s;e&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Dolores <HI>and</HI> Bribon <HI>run forward, and interrupt him.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am very anxious.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'd give half my e&s;tate to know it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lives linked together!&mdash;oh! I've heard of it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>So have I&mdash;it's a wonderful di&s;covery!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure it is.&mdash;Why, it accounts at once for tho&s;e cur&s;ed unprofitable apoplexies, What's that cat-o-nine tails?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="44" REF="50">
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>The&s;e varied coloured braids explain every thing as your books do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>By the&s;e knotty hieroglyphics, the necromancers expound the decrees of fate&mdash;Ob|&s;erve.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Keep off&mdash;I would not touch it for the world&mdash;the idea makes me paralytic. <Q REND="margQuotes">I hope my partner for life is one of the&s;e fine healthy Indians&mdash;long life to the worthy crea|tures &mdash;I love them in my heart, and &s;o I ought &mdash;are not all mankind a kin to one another?</Q></P>
</SP>
<Q REND="margQuotes"><SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>So Roldan and his crew &s;eem to think, for they treat the Indians exactly like poor relations.&mdash;</P>
</SP></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm exceedingly alarmed&mdash;wonder who they could find to couple with a lawyer's &s;oul.&mdash; Sweete&s;t of women&mdash;if you would conde&s;cend to enquire.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, if you would obtain from the necromancer one of the&s;e conjuring things, to inform me who is intere&s;ted in my unhappy lot, I'd pray for you&mdash;I'd go to the devil for you&mdash; I'd&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>And never again teaze me with love?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never&mdash;never.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll hate you as long as I live.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then meet me pre&s;ently&mdash;you &s;ee yonder cave.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's the dwelling of the necromancer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>I won't go there&mdash;I would not &s;ee his devil&s;hip for the fame of AE&s;culapius.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="45" REF="51">
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nor I, to be the Lycurgus of the new world.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well then, I'll take care you &s;hall not &s;ee him&mdash;&s;o, follow me, and I'll get you infor|mation will &s;et your hearts at ea&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bridon.</SPEAKER>
<P>I declare, what &s;he has &s;aid, has made me &s;o ill, I can &s;carce &s;tand&mdash;Oh, lord, I am afraid my accomplice is going.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, Bribon, forget and forgive&mdash; <STAGE>[gives him a phial]</STAGE> and, as you are ill, there's a pretty, ta&s;tele&s;s medicine that I'm &s;ure will do you good, my dear friend&mdash;Dam'me, but there's a do&s;e for you, however.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>A&s;ide and exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[to Herbert.]</STAGE>
<P>And does that old fool think I'd en&s;ure death by taking his cur&s;ed po|tions&mdash; ah, Sir, there is no way to deal with doctors.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>I beg your pardon, give them fees while you are well, and nothing when you are ill, and they are not the mi&s;chievous animals you think them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>If the necromancer will but &s;peak the truth&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! ha! already I've perform'd a miracle&mdash;for there go a phy&s;ician and a lawyer, wi&s;hing to &s;ind among men health and &s;incerity&mdash; This partner&s;hip of liver is a whim&s;ical kind of doctrine, and yet, ab&s;urd as it &s;eems, I feel it not altogether untrue, for were my Nelti to die, I believe, Herbert, thy life wou'd not be worth many days.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="46" REF="52">
<HEAD>SCENE IV.&mdash;<HI>The in&s;ide of an Indian hou&s;e.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Dolores.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>How anxious I am to know whom my precious life is joined to&mdash;Ah! here comes Nelti&mdash; Tell me, my dear girl&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Bribon.</STAGE>
<P>Get out of my way&mdash;</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you what, old Hellebore, I'll&mdash; Ah, here &s;he comes&mdash;now for it</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Nelti <HI>with a Quipos.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sweete&s;t me&s;&s;enger of fate, tell me the name of him, the chords of who&s;e heart are &s;o twi&s;t|ed with mine, that one crack will di&s;&s;ever both.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now attend&mdash;I &s;aid to the necromancer, Mo&s;t profound and learned &s;age, on who&s;e life depends that of old Doctor Dominic Dolores? &s;ays he, Has he not a decrepid form&mdash;withered face&mdash;&s;unk eyes&mdash;pug-no&s;e&mdash;paper lips&mdash;leather cheeks&mdash;&s;traggling teeth&mdash;&s;ays I, the de&s;cription &s;uits exactly&mdash;He then gave me this, which in|forms me your life is joined to&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Whom?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope &s;ome ra&s;cal, who will be hang'd in a week.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very likely, for it is joined to a lawyer's, and his name is&mdash;Bribon <STAGE>[with deliberation, and &s;eeming to expound the Quipos]</STAGE> when one dies, the other will inevitably expire.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, lud! Oh, lud!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolners.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, dear! Oh, dear!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="47" REF="53">
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ee I've made you quite happy&mdash;&s;o, good bye.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit laughing.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, cruel fate! that my precious life mu&s;t depend on my mortal enemy&mdash;I can't bear it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be in the &s;ame death-warrant with that old &s;uperannuated villain&mdash;Oh, 'tis too much!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[They each &s;it down lamenting, look at each other &s;ome time&mdash;fir&s;t, with fear and anxiety, &mdash;then they &s;mile and draw nearer to each other.]</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>I think it was ridiculous enough in us to quarrel about a &s;illy girl, Eh, Bribon?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very, Doctor; ju&s;t as if there were not unavoidable mi&s;eries enough in life, without mak|ing them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>True&mdash;how do you do?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>You don't look well.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear friend, let me feel your pul&s;e &mdash;Oh, lord, 'tis very quick.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Doctor, &s;it down.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ay, Bribon, you did not, (may be,) happen to &s;wallow the contents of the bottle I gave you</P>
<STAGE>[with he&s;itation.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, the &s;coundrel!&mdash; <STAGE>[a&s;ide]</STAGE>&mdash;Fir&s;t tell me how you are.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, independent of my care for you, I am very well&mdash;&s;o, you did not take the medicine? Well, its no great matter&mdash;I'm not offended with you&mdash;perhaps it is well as it is.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>What an old villain! If I thought it would not endanger his life, I would plague him
<PB N="48" REF="54">heartily <STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE> I don't think, my dear Doctor, you look ill.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ill! I never was better in my life</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Egad I will&mdash;I'll plague him <STAGE>[a&s;ide]</STAGE> and, thank heaven, the cordial you gave me, and which I have ju&s;t &s;wallowed&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[greatly alarm'd.]</STAGE>
<P>Why, you did not take it, did you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Every drop&mdash;I dare &s;ay it will do me infinite good.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, I dare &s;ay it will&mdash;let me feel your pul&s;e again&mdash;perhaps it may give you a bit of a twinge acro&s;s the &s;tomach&mdash;but don't mind it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;you &s;eem frighten'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not at all&mdash;don't agitate your&s;elf&mdash; let me feel your pul&s;e again&mdash;how lucky it is, my dear friend&mdash;any thing the matter?&mdash;How lucky, I &s;ay, that the lives of two men &s;hould be linked together, who love each other &s;o &s;incerely&mdash; Eh, what's the matter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing&mdash;I felt a little ugly pain, but its gone off&mdash;I can't help laughing to think we &s;hould quarrel about a girl&mdash;Ha, ha! ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha!&mdash;Oh, Lord! Ha, ha, ha! Are you &s;ure the pain's gone off&mdash;Ha, ha!&mdash;Oh, Lord! oh, dear!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, there again&mdash;they increa&s;e&mdash;they increa&s;e&mdash;Oh! oh!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am a mi&s;erable old man! What, again, Eh?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Have you any more of the bottle?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, no&mdash;I have a notion you have had enough of that.</P>
<STAGE>A&s;ide.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="49" REF="55">
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm torn to death&mdash;pray pre&s;cribe for me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Lord! not for the world&mdash;Leave it to nature&mdash;&s;he's the be&s;t phy&s;ician&mdash;Do you feel better?&mdash;I think you look better.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[&s;itting down on a chair.]</STAGE>
<P>I feel I am dying&mdash;as a proof of my love for you, Doctor, I bequeath you&mdash;(Oh!) all my property what|ever, and wi&s;h you a long and happy life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, zounds! you forget I &s;ha'n't out|live you a minute <STAGE>[Bribon <HI>appears convul&s;ed]</HI>&mdash;</STAGE> Oh! he's going&mdash;help! help!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Herbert <HI>(after having been peeping.)</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's all this bawling?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can nothing &s;ave my dear friend?&mdash; my life is wound up in his.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, poor Bribon! what, he's going&mdash;now, is not it a &s;hocking thing, Doctor, that, be|cau&s;e this &s;coundrel is dying, &s;ome amiable gen|tleman won't live half an hour?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, very &s;hocking! and between you and I, Herbert, I am that amiable, mi&s;erable old gentleman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>How will you part with Nelti?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pooh! &s;tuff&mdash;Do you think I mind parting with Nelti, or you, or all the world?&mdash;No; all my &s;truggles are, how to part with my &s;weet &s;elf, how to bid adieu to this dear, delicious little body&mdash;Oh! he's going&mdash;he's going.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can you do nothing for him?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bleeding,&mdash;bleeding's all that's left&mdash;If my hand's &s;teady enough, I'll open a vein.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="50" REF="56">
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be &s;ure you cut deep enough.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will&mdash;I will&mdash;but I hav'n't my in|&s;truments about me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here's my &s;word.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Give it me&mdash;I'll bleed him&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[jumping up.]</STAGE>
<P>No, you don't&mdash;don't be frightened <STAGE>[<HI>to</HI> Dolores]</STAGE> ble&s;s your &s;oul, it was all a fetch.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come to my arms <STAGE>[<HI>to</HI> Herbert]</STAGE> what are you grinning at?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, what are you&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll be revenged on him&mdash;I'll trick him out of Nelti yet.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>What?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll marry Nelti.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, are you mad? marry a young mettle&s;ome wench that&mdash;pooh&mdash;non&s;en&s;e&mdash;why, ar&s;enic wou'd not &s;end you to your grave with more expedition.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>True, Bribon&mdash;I'll go to Nelti&mdash;&s;o, farewell, Doctor.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Going.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;ha'n't&mdash;you &s;ha'n't&mdash;I demand &s;atisfaction&mdash;Oh, you cowardly&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Dolores <HI>attempts to follow him, which</HI> Bribon <HI>prevents</HI>&mdash;Herbert <HI>returns, in apparent anger; then</HI> Bribon <HI>&s;natches up</HI> Dolores <HI>in his arms, and runs off with him.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> Herbert, <HI>laughing.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>END OF THE FOURTH ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="act">
<PB N="51" REF="57">
<HEAD>ACT V.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE. I.&mdash;<HI>Out&s;ide of the Temple of the Sun.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Alonzo.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>STILL mu&s;t I wander near the&s;e awful walls, uncertain of my fate.&mdash;Though days and weeks pa&s;s on, yet nought I gain from lengthened time, but added woe.&mdash;Still, &s;till I tremble for her life! And were my mind relieved from that di&s;tracting fear, what comfort even then could reach me&mdash;The trea&s;ure of my &s;oul's immured in yon impenetrable &s;hrine&mdash;buried for ever in that grave of youth and beauty.&mdash;Where can I find a thought of ought but wretchedne&s;s&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Stands in a po&s;ture of de&s;pair.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Sola&s;co <HI>comes from the Temple and ob&s;erves</HI> Alonzo.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sola&s;co.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>What wou'd'&s;t thou?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sola&s;co.</SPEAKER>
<P>I come from Cora.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>From Cora &s;ay'&s;t thou? I dread&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sola&s;co.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dread the wor&s;t.&mdash;The haple&s;s victim of unholy love &s;ends to Alonzo her dying ble&s;&s;ing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh heaven!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sola&s;co.</SPEAKER>
<P>Her ab&s;ence from the temple was di&s;|covered.&mdash;She was &s;een with thee.&mdash;She begged
<PB N="52" REF="58">me to conjure thee by her love, to &s;ave thy&s;elf from death by in&s;tant flight&mdash;obey her quickly&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Going.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stay, &s;tay I charge thee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sola&s;co.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have performed my office; urge not my &s;tay, for I have feelings hard to be &s;uppre&s;&s;ed, and which, if not &s;uppre&s;&s;ed, might wound thee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>What can now wound me more?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sola&s;co.</SPEAKER>
<P>We thought thee perfect, we adored thee with reverence, fit only for the power who&s;e wor&s;hip thou ha&s;t violated.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Forbear old man; cea&s;e thy untimely chidings.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sola&s;co.</SPEAKER>
<P>My woes may &s;urely ju&s;tify my chid|ings. &mdash; <Q REND="margQuotes">I, who behold a race, in which each virtue heaven could give, all honour human power could be&s;tow, has bloomed for ages, bla&s;ted with infamy, with infamy by thee.</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>"Forbear, forbear."&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sola&s;co.</SPEAKER>
<P>I, who am doomed to view the deare&s;t object of my doating fondne&s;s, who&s;e goodne&s;s oft' has &s;teeped the&s;e aged eyes in tears of joy, to &s;ee her branded with guilt, devoted to de|&s;truction.&mdash;Have not I full cau&s;e, thus loudly to complain, and to upbraid thee, &mdash;I, her haple&s;s father?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Father &s;ay'&s;t thou? <STAGE>[falling on his knees]</STAGE> Thou, the father of my Cora.&mdash; <Q REND="margQuotes">Oh forgive me; yet how can'&s;t thou forgive the murderer of thy child? Strike, &s;trike this weapon in my guilty brea&s;t&mdash;Oh give me death; it will at once to thee be vengeance, and to me be mercy.</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="53" REF="59">
<SPEAKER>Sola&s;co.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q REND="margQuotes">I &s;eek not vengeance; vengeance is for weaker woes.&mdash;But tell me, how could'&s;t thou heap &s;uch angui&s;h on a heart that never injured thee?</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q REND="margQuotes">Oh father, let me call thee &s;o&mdash; wring not my &s;oul thus</Q>&mdash;I love thy daughter with a flame pure as her virtues; think then what I mu&s;t feel, and even thou may'&s;t pity me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sola&s;co.</SPEAKER>
<P>If thou do&s;t truly love my haple&s;s child, e'en in the mid&s;t of all my woes, my bo|&s;om owns one pang for thee&mdash;The torments of my Cora &s;oon mu&s;t end.&mdash;Thine, alas!&mdash;but let me not encrea&s;e the &s;orrows I could wi&s;h to &s;oothe &mdash;Farewell&mdash;obey my dying child, and grant her all the joy &s;he now can ta&s;te&mdash;to know that thou art &s;afe.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Think'&s;t thou I am ba&s;e enough to live the monument of her de&s;truction, and my own di&s;grace.&mdash;No, if <HI>my</HI> life cannot alone appea&s;e your violated laws, let me at lea&s;t partake my Cora's doom, and in a fond embrace expiring, I'll ble&s;s the fate, that e'en in death unites us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sola&s;co.</SPEAKER>
<P>Our law allows no partial mitigation&mdash; leave her to meet the doom thou can'&s;t not &s;ave her from; and do thou bear life a little longer, to give unhappy Cora, in her dying pangs, one ray of comfort.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh my father!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sola&s;co.</SPEAKER>
<P>Farewell, farewell my &s;on; and if thou can'&s;t be happy, heaven can tell I wi&s;h thee &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now then the &s;um of horror is com|plete.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Indian in&s;trument &s;ounds.</STAGE>
<STAGE><PB N="54" REF="60">
<HI>Enter</HI> Orozimbo <HI>attended.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo, thy aid is now our chief reliance&mdash;Roldan prepares to attack us; and &s;ince the good Columbus left our coa&s;t, thro' many tedious months of care and danger, thy coun&s;el and thy valour, &s;till have been defence and &s;afety to us. But, why droops the brave Alonzo?&mdash; If any tender &s;cruple of &s;hedding native blood now check thy wonted ardour, freely avow the generous weakne&s;s, &mdash;On thee depends our fate&mdash; yet would I welcome the lo&s;s of empire and of life, rather than &s;ave them by Alonzo's mi&s;ery.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;With hone&s;t zeal I draw my &s;word again&s;t the enemies of innocence, tho' the &s;ame clime hath bred us.&mdash;He who regards his coun|try's real honour, owns for his countrymen, none but the virtuous.&mdash;Yet, Orozimbo, this heart is bur&s;ting with its angui&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thy &s;orrows, tho' I am uncon&s;cious of the cau&s;e, have found their way into my kin|dred brea&s;t.&mdash;Tell me thy griefs, that I may &s;oothe, perhaps relieve them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou, thou alone ha&s;t power to do it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, by my kingdom, thou &s;halt find relief.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[Looking round]</STAGE>
<P>Command that all re|main at di&s;tance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Retire!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Troops retreat to the back of the &s;tage.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[Points to the Temple]</STAGE>
<P>Behold tho&s;e walls! does thy exalted mind, which owns the noble&s;t energies of rea&s;on, does it approve that &s;tructure, reared by mi&s;taken zeal, to glorify the Deity, by the dire &s;acrifice of all his deare&s;t ble&s;&s;ings?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="55" REF="61">
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Say on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Does &s;he, who, in the prime of youth, when every fine affection of the &s;oul glows with its noble&s;t fervour, when all the joys of life &s;eem decked with magic &s;plendour, does &s;he de&s;erve the puni&s;hment of guilt, who, buried in yon' ruthle&s;s pri&s;on, ca&s;ts a fond thought on the de|lights &s;he has lo&s;t, dares to condemn the tyranny which binds her, and claims her right to liberty and love?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I would a&s;pire to reign beyond the limits of weak prejudice; but reflect, Alonzo, how &s;acred are a country's cu&s;toms.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>There, there's the &s;ource of half the mi&s;ery of human kind&mdash;cu&s;tom is the vile con|founder of virtue and of vice.&mdash;It checks the operation of our godlike rea&s;on, and makes the greate&s;t glory of creation, a being void of will&mdash; Oh, Orozimbo, &s;oar &s;uperior to the mi&s;ts of error &mdash;when thy great &s;oul di&s;plays unmanacled its glo|rious attributes&mdash;thou'lt cea&s;e to think that God delights in cruelty, who&s;e ble&s;t infu&s;ion in the human heart breathes mercy and benevolence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oft have I admired thy wi&s;dom and thy virtue; but, now methinks, in thee I hear the voice of heaven, and it &s;hall be obeyed.&mdash; But I mu&s;t prai&s;e thy wonderous goodne&s;s, which can thus plead for other's mi&s;ery.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>There I am unworthy of thy prai&s;e&mdash; mine is a &s;elfi&s;h zeal&mdash;I've &s;ued for one whom I adore; nay for my&s;elf I've &s;ued.&mdash;Oh, Orozimbo, in the repeal of an inhuman law, thou ha&s;t re|&s;tored my forfeit life&mdash;nay more&mdash;the life of her I love.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>What do I hear?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="56" REF="62"><HI>Enter</HI> Cuto.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cuto.</SPEAKER>
<P>Great chief, the foe is on their march&mdash; your warriors are a&s;&s;embled, anxious for your pre|&s;ence to lead them to victory.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>On my friends.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>One moment &s;tay.&mdash;Le&s;t the fell chance of war (which, heaven avert) &s;hou'd leave my lovely Cora without the generous friend &s;he has found in thee; fir&s;t let me bear your royal mandate to the temple, &s;trictly commanding, (whatever fate may in the battle wait us) pardon and liberty for her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mu&s;t in per&s;on give the important mandate&mdash;Lead on the troops <STAGE>[to Alonzo,]</STAGE> and I with &s;peed will join you. <STAGE>[to the troops.]</STAGE> I leave you to the conduct of the brave Alonzo.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Orozimbo <HI>goes towards the temple,</HI> Alonzo <HI>heads the troops</HI>&mdash;</STAGE>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE III. <HI>A Battle.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Excur&s;ions</HI>&mdash;Alonzo <HI>is &s;een &s;ucce&s;sfully to attack</HI> Roldan, <HI>who is relieved by a party of Spaniards</HI> &mdash;Alonzo <HI>retreats fighting&mdash;Indians driven acro&s;s the &s;tage.]</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Orozimbo, <HI>attended, and</HI> Herbert.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alas! our efforts are, I fear, in vain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>We'll fight, my noble chief, 'till we force victory to crown us&mdash;our deeds &s;hall &s;hame her for inclining to our da&s;tard enemies&mdash;Alonzo bears about him like an hungry lion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heaven protect and aid him.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<PB N="57" REF="63">
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>What an unlucky dog am I&mdash;I was within &s;ix yards of that de&s;troyer of innocents, Roldan, and yet the villain had the good luck to e&s;cape me&mdash;I have not had a bit of fighting &s;o long, and this whet has given me &s;uch an appe|tite&mdash;ha, ha! here comes work for me&mdash;now, my boy, Herbert, &s;tick to them.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter two Spaniards.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Spaniard.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yield directly, you Engli&s;h de|&s;erter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I am a de&s;erter; but there alone where an Engli&s;hman will be one, from villainy and oppre&s;&s;ion to honour and humanity&mdash;Have at you, bloodhounds!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>[They fight, &s;eize Herbert's &s;word-arm, and force him off the &s;tage; during which</HI> Nelti <HI>enters in the dre&s;s of a female warrior.]</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Herbert in danger <STAGE>[draws her bow]</STAGE> Aid me, ye powers! <STAGE>[he&s;itates]</STAGE> Alas! his manly brea&s;t pre&s;ents it&s;elf, and my erring hand may &s;lay my love&mdash;They overpower him&mdash;now, heaven direct me <STAGE>[&s;he lets fly an arrow]</STAGE>&mdash;he's &s;afe&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>[falls on her knees.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Re-enter</HI> Herbert, <HI>driving a Spaniard acro&s;s the &s;tage.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Saved by a woman's hand!&mdash;&s;he faints &mdash;the &s;pirit which animated her to pre&s;erve me, now &s;inks beneath the weight of its own effort&mdash; Good heaven! can it be?&mdash;'Tis Nelti.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Hugging her.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Herbert, joy has almo&s;t the &s;ame effect that terror had, and I am &s;carce able to bear the exce&s;s of happine&s;s your &s;afety gives me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="58" REF="64">
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear angelic girl, I am in &s;uch tran&s;port, I &s;carcely know, whether I am in earth or in heaven. <STAGE>[&s;houts.]</STAGE> But let me be&s;tow you in a place of &s;afety, for you hear I am wanted.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then my bu&s;ines is not done&mdash;I came here to watch your &s;afety, and I'll not leave you; &s;o, obey me&mdash;you are not the fir&s;t hero who has had a female commander.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then act, my love, like a commander, and get out of the reach of danger as fa&s;t as you can&mdash;See how the Indians fly&mdash;Hah! we are &s;ur|prized, and our retreat cut off&mdash;This way&mdash;this way&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt, [a troop of Spaniards pur&s;uing.]</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE THE LAST.&mdash;<HI>A garden of the Temple of the Sun&mdash;at the upper end an arch.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Catalpo <HI>and prie&s;ts.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Catalpo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tho' I receiv'd, with all apparent re|verence, the mandate of the King, to &s;pare the impious prie&s;te&s;s, I but di&s;&s;embled, to pre&s;erve our &s;acred rites inviolate&mdash;had I oppo&s;ed the hated order, his power would have re&s;cued from our gra&s;p, the object of our vengeance.</P>
</SP>
<Q REND="margQuotes"><SP>
<SPEAKER>Prie&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, &s;ay, Catalpo, does no doubt re|main of this young prie&s;te&s;s' crime! For, by our chief's command to &s;pare her life, he &s;urely <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> her innocent.</P>
</SP></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>"Catalpo.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q REND="margQuotes">There can exi&s;t no doubt&mdash;On the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> which followed that dreadful night, when <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">e dire war of elements diffu&s;ed &s;uch general horror, Ble&s;&s;co, who&s;e truth none yet e'er doubt|ed, beheld her conducted to the temple by one of the&s;e hated &s;trangers, with whom &s;he parted
<PB N="59" REF="65">with every mark of fond endearment&mdash;Long he concealed this, till at length his con&s;cience &s;ore|ly wounded by the guilt he &s;ecreted, he on his oath declared to me this profanation.</Q> In&s;tant conduct the offender to her doom.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter prie&s;ts, conducting</HI> Cora <HI>in proce&s;&s;ion, with ar|chers and</HI> Sola&s;co.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sola&s;co. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[falling on his knees.]</STAGE>
<P>Oh, reverend prie&s;t, on my devoted head let fall the vengeance of the offended law&mdash;the crime was mine; I heeded not the tears which trickled down my Cora's angel-face; I li&s;tened not to the reproving &s;ighs, which forced their way from her lament|ing bo&s;om; but, deaf to nature's voice, com|pelled her to dedicate her youth to &s;olitude and mi&s;ery.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Catalpo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hence, nor offer further in&s;ult to of|fended heaven, by pleading for a wretch who braves its laws.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sola&s;co.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sure heaven will pardon a poor old man, who pleads for mercy to his child&mdash;the of|fence was mine, then take my forfeit life, but &s;ave, O &s;ave my Cora.</P>
</SP>
<Q REND="margQuotes"><SP>
<SPEAKER>Catalpo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Retire; for tho' no pray'rs &s;hall urge me to neglect the duty which I owe to heaven, I do not wi&s;h a father's eyes to view the &s;hed|ding of his daughter's blood.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sola&s;co.</SPEAKER>
<P>And does thy piety, thy filial love, then doom thee to de&s;truction? Cur&s;ed Sola&s;co! how worthle&s;s art thou of thy child&mdash;thy inju&s;|tice devoted her to mi&s;ery, and in return &s;he dooms her&s;elf to death, to &s;ave her cruel fa|ther's life.</P>
</SP></Q>
<STAGE>[Cora <HI>throws her&s;elf round his neck.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<PB N="60" REF="66">
<SPEAKER>Catalpo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dost thou &s;till with impious &s;tubborn|ne&s;s, per&s;i&s;t to keep concealed the partner of thy guilt? Say, who it was &s;educed thy innocence?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, for mercy, &s;pare me &s;o dire a thought&mdash;Shall I be his accu&s;er&mdash;Oh ble&s;s, pre|&s;erve him, Heaven.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Catalpo.</SPEAKER>
<P>This in&s;tant meet thy fate.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Cuto.</STAGE>
<P>What ra&s;h foot dares, unbidden, to approach the &s;acred Temple?</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cuto.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h my tidings did not ju&s;tify in|tru&s;ion &mdash;Reverend Prie&s;t, freedom is lo&s;t&mdash;the barbarous foe hath conquered.</P>
</SP>
<SP REND="margQuotes">
<SPEAKER>Catalpo. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[to Cora]</STAGE>
<P><Q>Thou ha&s;t armed the hand of Heaven again&s;t us&mdash;its indignation falls on ourheads in vengeance for thy crime</Q>&mdash;Lead to her death.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[as they &s;eize her]</STAGE>
<P>Hold&mdash;doth Alonzo live?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cuto.</SPEAKER>
<P>He was too brave for life&mdash;With ardour more than human he &s;ought the fierce&s;t dangers of the fight, and hurled de&s;truction round him; but at length hemmed in by numbers more than mortal arm could force, he mu&s;t have fallen, to &s;well the horrors of this dreadful day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then welcome, death</P>
<STAGE>[fixed in a po&s;ture of de&s;pair]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Catalpo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! it mu&s;t be &s;o&mdash;the &s;ecret is re|vealed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lead me to my fate&mdash;Your cruelty will now be mercy&mdash;My &s;oul's impatient to throw off this load of life, eager to join the &s;pirit of my lord, and &s;oar in union to the realms of bli&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="61" REF="67">
<SPEAKER>Catalpo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Silence this frenzy&mdash;or if thou mu&s;t be loud in exclamation, cur&s;e with your dying breath your impious violator.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Peace, mon&s;ter, dare not to breathe a &s;ound reproachful to my Alonzo's memory, le&s;t I forget the calm &s;olemnity this awful moment claims, and pour on thee my cur&s;es.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Catalpo.</SPEAKER>
<P>To death with her, and thou, old man, this in&s;tant quit the Temple, or behold thy daughter bleed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sola&s;co.</SPEAKER>
<P>Farewell, my child, I'll weep no more. &mdash;This bur&s;ting heart will &s;oon force out a pa&s;|&s;age for my &s;oul to take its &s;light and follow thee.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Embraces Cora and Exit.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>The ceremony takes place, the Archers range, and Cora is led to the upper part of the &s;tage&mdash;The Archers draw their arrows, then Alonzo ru&s;hes down, covers her with his &s;hield, and exclaims</HI> Hold, mon&s;ters, hold! <HI>They are a&s;toni&s;hed at the appearance of Alonzo and drop their bows&mdash; Cora &s;aints, Alonzo bears her forward.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>My life, my Cora&mdash;Could their barba|rian hands dare point their vengeance at thy love|ly form? And have I then the bli&s;s to cla&s;p thee once again&mdash;Tho' danger, and tho' death on every &s;ide &s;urround us, &s;till to enfold thee thus is extacy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>My loved Alonzo&mdash;They told me thou wen't dead, and I was eager to e&s;cape from life, again to meet thee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>By miracle hath Heaven pre&s;erved me&mdash; But &s;ay, what meant tho&s;e bloody rites?</P>
<STAGE>[to Ca|talpo]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Catalpo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Think not thy frenzy &s;hall impede our ju&s;tice.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="62" REF="68"><HI>[Orozimbo without]</HI></STAGE>
<P>Make fa&s;t the Temple gates&mdash;The foe will &s;oon be here <STAGE>[comes forward]</STAGE> Alonzo&mdash;do&s;t thou live, my friend?</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>The arm of heaven was &s;urely &s;tretched to &s;ave me&mdash;I forced my way thro' the oppo&s;ing multitude, and &s;eeing all was lo&s;t, I came once more to view this precious trea&s;ure, and die de|fending it&mdash;here I met death in all his dire&s;t hor|ror, cloathed in the garb of prie&s;tly cruelty, not even thy command&mdash;their king's decree, could &s;top the torrent of their barbarous zeal.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou traitor&mdash;hence from my &s;ight &mdash;begone&mdash; <STAGE>[Exit Catalpo]</STAGE>&mdash;death waits us all&mdash; let's meet it as we ought.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Di&s;tant &s;houts.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! what a moment of di&s;traction&mdash; mu&s;t I behold thee&mdash;[<HI>to</HI> Cora] &s;inking beneath the weight of butchering &s;words, or wor&s;e, leave thee the victim of a brutal conqueror.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can my Alonzo grudge me the bli&s;s to die with him&mdash;&s;ouls linked like ours, the call of death &s;hould never &s;ummon &s;ingly.&mdash;The hor|rors of captivity, thou need'&s;t not dread for me. &mdash;This <STAGE>[<HI>&s;natching</HI> Alonzo's <HI>poignard</HI>]</STAGE> if the &s;abres of the foe &s;hrink from &s;hedding a woman's blood, this &s;hall prevent my lingering in life, when my dear lord has left it.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Noi&s;e at the gate of the Temple and &s;houts.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>They come&mdash;now then for death.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[Embraces <HI>Alonzo</HI> and <HI>Cora</HI>]</STAGE>
<P>Fare|well&mdash;farewell.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>They all &s;tand in po&s;tures of defence; a noi&s;e is heard like the bur&s;ting of a gate,</HI> Herbert <HI>ru&s;hes in.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<PB N="63" REF="69">
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Huzza! victory! victory!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Herbert!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[comes down]</STAGE>
<P>Victory!&mdash;ju&s;tice&mdash;hap|pine&s;s. &mdash; <STAGE>[<HI>embraces</HI> Alonzo]</STAGE> huzza!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>In&s;tant ea&s;e this anxious heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Give me breath <STAGE>[&s;houts without]</STAGE> huz|za! &mdash;now for it&mdash;in our late overthrow, finding our retreat cut off, Nelti and I &s;campered towards the &s;hore, with a troop of the whi&s;kered blood|hounds at our heels.&mdash;There, to my &s;urprize I beheld a fleet&mdash;Spani&s;h colours&mdash;they were land|ing &mdash;I hailed the fir&s;t boat&mdash;Who's your admiral &s;ays I&mdash;Columbus!&mdash;Columbus!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Orozimbo</HI> and <HI>Alonzo.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Columbus&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ay, Columbus&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, Spain, thou ha&s;t retrieved thy name.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who's your admiral, &s;ays I&mdash;Co|lumbus.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Say on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>He landed, and when I had done crying, I informed him what had happened.&mdash; On the in&s;tant his troops flew to arms.&mdash;But Rol|dan's crew &s;aved us the trouble of fighting&mdash;they fell on their coward knees <STAGE>[&s;houts]</STAGE> but here they come, and as they ought&mdash;Roldan in chains, and Columbus triumphant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hear'&s;t thou, my love&mdash;let the&s;e de|lightful &s;ounds di&s;pel the hideous horrors which oppre&s;&s;ed thee, and elevate thy &s;oul, like mine, to heavenly bli&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bli&s;s Alonzo! Can happine&s;s be ours?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>For ever.</P>
<STAGE>[Embraces her.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="64" REF="70">
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Receive, Alonzo, receive thy Cora to thy arms, and may the giver of all bli&s;s &s;hower down upon your faithful loves, his choice&s;t ble&s;|&s;ings.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter in proce&s;&s;ion&mdash;Trumpeters&mdash;Spani&s;h &s;ol|diers&mdash;Others bearing pre&s;ents&mdash;Models of guns&mdash; Sailors with model of a &s;hip&mdash; Monks bearing the bible and cro&s;s&mdash;Spani&s;h banners &mdash; Dolores and Bribon&mdash;Spani&s;h &s;oldiers&mdash;Roldan, Mo&s;co&s;o, and Spani&s;h &s;oldiers, chained&mdash; Sola&s;co &mdash; Nelti, with Indian women &s;cattering flowers&mdash;Banner of the order of Alcantara&mdash;Attendants bearing in&s;ignia &mdash;Columbus.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, my dear country, for I mu&s;t call thee mine, do I again behold thee? This happy hour o'erpays my utmo&s;t toil.&mdash;My friends, much have I to enquire.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Great Columbus, till my heart is made acquainted with thy fortunes, I cannot tell thee of my happine&s;s&mdash;Has Spain redre&s;&s;ed thy in|juries &mdash; has Ferdinand &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo, my wrongs were enviable&mdash; captivity was triumph &mdash; When amid&s;t the ap|plauding &s;houts of thou&s;ands, I approached the royal pre&s;ence, the &s;uffering monarch &s;hrunk from the fight, and threw his mantle o'er his face, crim&s;oned with &s;hame; then rai&s;ed me to his arms, &s;till my pride &s;u&s;tained me; but when I beheld the beauteous I&s;abella, try to force from their dire gra&s;p my galling chains, and on each wound drop a balmy tear, loyalty and love ruthed on my &s;oul, I embraced her royal feet, and gave her tears for thanks; then all the pride of pa|geantry was decreed, but my &s;oul langui&s;hed for
<PB N="65" REF="71">the time, when, Orozimbo, I might thus again enfold thee, and re&s;tore to thee thy kingdom, freed from the gripe of ruthle&s;s tyranny.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orozimbo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Greate&s;t of men, in firme&s;t confi|dence of thy excelling virtues, I repo&s;e my peo|ple's &s;afety.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[to Herbert]</STAGE>
<P>My noble Engli&s;hman, receive from my hand this lovely maid, and &s;uch benefits as I can be&s;tow, you may command.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Talks apart with</HI> Orozimbo, Alonzo, <HI>and</HI> Cora.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now, my dear Herbert, you will be|come a great man, and live at your ea&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>A great man, and be at ea&s;e!&mdash;never was &s;uch a thing heard of. This is the &s;ort of being which pa&s;&s;es for a great man, and I hope you don't call this being at ea&s;e&mdash; <STAGE>[Erects his head, and walks about &s;truttingly.]</STAGE>&mdash;Ha, ha! No, my love, it requires a cur&s;ed deal more hard la|bour to impo&s;e on the world, than &s;uits the tran|quil indolence of my di&s;po&s;ition. And now, that all may this day be happy, Doctor, a word with you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[running before Dolores.]</STAGE>
<P>What do you want, Sir, with my friend?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, what do you want?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Only this, my excellent friends, I have abu&s;ed your credulity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>How?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Herbert.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your lives are independent of each other, and now you may hate him again as heartily as ever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dolores</SPEAKER>
<P>Did not the necromancer?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nelti.</SPEAKER>
<P>I was the necromancer, old Dominic.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="66" REF="72">
<SPEAKER>Dolores.</SPEAKER>
<P>You were&mdash;Get out of my way, you&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Kicks at</HI> Bribon.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bribon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Snaps his fingers at</HI> Doroles.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Columbus <HI>and the re&s;t come forward.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Columbus.</SPEAKER>
<P>That was indeed a triumph.&mdash;See tho&s;e wretches clo&s;ely guarded&mdash;their puni&s;hment mu&s;t not now damp the joy I feel. Oh, were I &s;a|tisfied no future Roldans would alarm your peace, I &s;hould be ble&s;t indeed.&mdash;Had I earlier known that Englands monarch would have graced my fortunes with his victorious banner, then would your freedom been firmly &s;ixed.&mdash;They only, who them&s;elves are free, give liberty to others.</P>
<L>BRITONS again behold Columbus &s;ue</L>
<L>To have his fortunes patronized by you;</L>
<L>To your &s;upport alone he tru&s;ts his cau&s;e,</L>
<L>And re&s;ts his fame, on Engli&s;hmens applau&s;e.</L>
</SP>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<TRAILER>FINIS.</TRAILER>
</DIV1>
