<BACK>
<DIV1 TYPE="epilogue">
<PB REF="73">
<HEAD>EPILOGUE.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>WRITTEN BY MILES P. ANDREWS, ESQ. SPOKEN BY MRS. POPE.</BYLINE>
<SP>
<LG>
<L>OLD &s;tories done&mdash;old times long &s;ince forgotten,</L>
<L>Like mu&s;ty records, little read, and rotten,</L>
<L>Return we now, to periods &s;ounder grown,</L>
<L>To happier days, and readings of our own;</L>
<L>Where'er we ope the book, the &s;tile is clear,</L>
<L>The int're&s;t charming, the conclu&s;ions, dear;</L>
<L>Our means are flouri&s;hing, our joys not &s;cant,</L>
<L>Po&s;&s;e&s;s'd of every good, the heart can want,</L>
<L>Old tales of conque&s;ts, thrown on di&s;tant &s;helves,</L>
<L>We've little left to conquer&mdash;but our&s;elves:&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>An arduous ta&s;k&mdash;and yet to do us right,</L>
<L>We lo&s;e no time in entering on the fight;</L>
<L>Mi&s;s, &s;carcely in her teens, attacks Mama,</L>
<L>Already having routed <HI>&s;age</HI> Papa;</L>
<L>"I'm not a chit&mdash;I <HI>will</HI> turn up my locks, &mdash;</L>
<L>"I <HI>will</HI> wear powder, and I <HI>won't</HI> wear frocks;&mdash;</L>
<L>"I hate to dance with <HI>boys,</HI> now I'm &s;o tall,</L>
<L>"I'm fit for <HI>any man,</HI> at <HI>any ball;</HI>&mdash;</L>
<L>"You want to keep me back, becau&s;e its known,</L>
<L>"When girls <HI>grow up,</HI> their mothers, they <HI>grow down."</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Pert Ma&s;ter Bobby too, releas'd from &s;chool,</L>
<L>Hectors at home, and early learns to rule;</L>
<L>The &s;plendid &s;tud, relinqui&s;h'd by his &s;ire,</L>
<L>In grand di&s;play, awaits the youthful Squire;</L>
<L>And while to Cambridge he &s;hould &s;tudious &s;teer,</L>
<L>New market's cour&s;e arre&s;ts his gay career;</L>
<L><PB REF="74">There he, <HI>long odds, &s;hort betts, pa&s;s dice,</HI> all pat in,</L>
<L>Sticks to the <HI>Greeks,</HI> and di&s;regards the Latin;</L>
<L>Flown up to town, our fierce-cock'd, <HI>captious</HI> Bobby,</L>
<L>Drives to the play, and quarrels in the lobby;</L>
<L>"Sir, you're a &s;coundrel! damme Sir, you lie"&mdash;</L>
<L>"Sir, here's my <HI>card,</HI> for <HI>damme I am&mdash;I."&mdash;</HI></L>
<L>Thus is the boy, intent to ape the man,</L>
<L>A puff of di&s;cord, and a fla&s;h in pan.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>In married life, re&s;olving each to drive,</L>
<L>A &s;weet contention keeps the flame alive;</L>
<L>"I know my province&mdash;&s;o do I, my Lady&mdash;</L>
<L>"You'll prove my torment&mdash;you've proved mine al|ready.</L>
<L>"To guard my rights, my Lord, I mu&s;t endeavour&mdash;</L>
<L>"You're always out&mdash;and you are out for ever&mdash;</L>
<L>"Then both I tru&s;t are happy, <HI>&s;po&s;o caro</HI>&mdash; <STAGE>with ironical tenderne&s;s)</STAGE></L>
<L>"You throw at <HI>hazard,</HI> and I punt at <HI>pharo;</HI></L>
<L>"Each have their object&mdash;&s;o re&s;entment &s;mother&mdash;</L>
<L>"Hold out the olive <HI>branch,</HI> or wear another."</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Suffice this raillery&mdash;enough to prove,</L>
<L>Our noble&s;t conque&s;t, is our own &s;elf-love;</L>
<L>The Author, who to night has greatly dar'd,</L>
<L>To brave the i&s;&s;ue of your high award;</L>
<L>Tho' old, the legend whence his &s;cenes he drew,</L>
<L>Humbly pre&s;umes, the in&s;erence may be new;</L>
<L>Should then the efforts of his untaught mu&s;e,</L>
<L>By ju&s;t, tho' &s;mall de&s;ert, his flights excu&s;e;</L>
<L>Let him enjoy, for all his anxious toils,</L>
<L>That bright reward&mdash;the triumph of your &s;miles.</L>
</LG>
</SP>
</DIV1>
